1
00:00:01,060 --> 00:00:06,126
[SPEAKER_05]: Good evening and welcome to May vs Corbin live, the battle for number 10.

2
00:00:07,017 --> 00:00:14,508
[SPEAKER_06]: Over the next 90 minutes, we'll see what the Prime Minister, Theresa May, and Labour's leader, Jeremy Corbyn, are really made of.

3
00:00:15,369 --> 00:00:23,121
[SPEAKER_05]: Our live studio audience will be asking the questions they and you want answered direct to Mrs May and Mr Corbyn.

4
00:00:23,681 --> 00:00:31,573
[SPEAKER_06]: And I'll be interviewing them both about their policies, their leadership, and their vision for the future of a post-Brexit United Kingdom.

5
00:00:32,127 --> 00:00:35,595
[SPEAKER_05]: The Labour leader arrived here in West London a short time ago.

6
00:00:35,635 --> 00:00:39,264
[SPEAKER_05]: He'll be first to face our audience in just a moment.

7
00:00:39,965 --> 00:00:41,930
[SPEAKER_05]: And the Conservative leader is here too.

8
00:00:42,291 --> 00:00:46,560
[SPEAKER_05]: Both are preparing for an evening that could define the rest of the campaign.

9
00:00:47,523 --> 00:00:50,710
[SPEAKER_05]: The battle for number 10 is here and now.

10
00:01:02,620 --> 00:01:16,123
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's get things started then and introduce the leader of the Labour Party, Jeremy Corbyn.

11
00:01:18,787 --> 00:01:23,936
[SPEAKER_05]: At this point, I should point out that the audience members have been carefully selected to provide balance.

12
00:01:24,056 --> 00:01:29,285
[SPEAKER_05]: A third are declared Conservative supporters, a third are for Labour, and a third are undecided.

13
00:01:29,325 --> 00:01:33,152
[SPEAKER_05]: So let's get started with our first question, which comes from Ines.

14
00:01:33,392 --> 00:01:33,893
[SPEAKER_05]: Ines.

15
00:01:34,480 --> 00:01:47,916
[SPEAKER_07]: Mr Corbyn, in your speech following the Manchester attack last Friday, you stated that no government can prevent every terrorist attack and that we need a foreign policy that reduces rather than increases the threat to this country.

16
00:01:48,557 --> 00:01:54,404
[SPEAKER_07]: Islamic State have clearly stated that anyone who doesn't abide by their ideology is their enemy.

17
00:01:54,765 --> 00:02:01,433
[SPEAKER_07]: So why should we soften our foreign policy if it is blatantly obvious that there is no room for negotiation?

18
00:02:02,020 --> 00:02:04,083
[SPEAKER_03]: It's not about softening our foreign policy.

19
00:02:04,123 --> 00:02:07,328
[SPEAKER_03]: It is about absolutely condemning what happened in Manchester.

20
00:02:07,709 --> 00:02:12,216
[SPEAKER_03]: Innocent lives were taken, young women and girls out enjoying themselves for the evening.

21
00:02:12,516 --> 00:02:13,858
[SPEAKER_03]: That's the society we live in.

22
00:02:13,899 --> 00:02:15,741
[SPEAKER_03]: That's the society I want to live in.

23
00:02:16,142 --> 00:02:19,007
[SPEAKER_03]: And nobody should be allowed to take that away from anybody.

24
00:02:19,527 --> 00:02:26,679
[SPEAKER_03]: The person who committed it did an appalling and abominable atrocious act, as did apparently those that were conspiring with him.

25
00:02:26,719 --> 00:02:29,563
[SPEAKER_03]: The police investigation is ongoing.

26
00:02:29,543 --> 00:02:50,962
[SPEAKER_03]: My point was that we have to have a foreign policy around the world that doesn't leave large areas without any effective government, such as in Libya at the present time, which can become a breeding ground of a place of enormous danger to all of us and indeed any Western country in Europe or in North America.

27
00:02:51,223 --> 00:02:53,465
[SPEAKER_03]: My point was absolute condemnation.

28
00:02:53,865 --> 00:02:56,567
[SPEAKER_03]: My point was that we need more police, not less.

29
00:02:56,868 --> 00:02:59,550
[SPEAKER_03]: That's why we pledged to provide 10,000

30
00:02:59,530 --> 00:03:10,809
[SPEAKER_03]: more police on our streets and that we wanted a foreign policy that didn't leave large areas of the world ungoverned so that we had a more secure future for all of us.

31
00:03:11,631 --> 00:03:18,703
[SPEAKER_03]: And do not allow this to become an attack on our multicultural society or on

32
00:03:18,683 --> 00:03:20,826
[SPEAKER_03]: the wonderful faith of Islam.

33
00:03:20,846 --> 00:03:26,575
[SPEAKER_03]: This is a perversion of Islam, what was done in Manchester, as indeed other attacks have been.

34
00:03:26,836 --> 00:03:43,982
[SPEAKER_03]: What we need is a strategy that protects us, but a foreign policy that engages with the rest of the world as well, to bring about a safer world for all of us.

35
00:03:44,992 --> 00:03:59,406
[SPEAKER_07]: I think it's just in terms of foreign policy, you know, are you going to look the other way if there's any military intervention that is needed in that area to support the coalition that are fighting IS?

36
00:03:59,588 --> 00:04:08,486
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, the coalitions that are dealing with IS in Syria are complex and they're sometimes fighting each other as well.

37
00:04:08,987 --> 00:04:16,382
[SPEAKER_03]: My whole point is that we have to cut off the funds for IS, cut off the arms for IS, cut off their

38
00:04:16,362 --> 00:04:40,977
[SPEAKER_03]: publicity as far as we can but also bring about a peace process in Syria by reconvening the Geneva talks including all the neighboring countries as well as Iran but also bring about a constructive dialogue in Libya so that we don't have huge areas of that country with all its oil wealth underneath it ungoverned and a prey for this kind of thing.

39
00:04:41,177 --> 00:04:42,960
[SPEAKER_03]: There are desperate people in Libya

40
00:04:42,940 --> 00:04:44,322
[SPEAKER_03]: living in refugee camps.

41
00:04:44,643 --> 00:04:49,492
[SPEAKER_03]: Let's give them something positive and some hope by bringing about stability in that country.

42
00:04:49,552 --> 00:05:01,573
[SPEAKER_03]: It's up to all of us to engage with that because if there is ungoverned spaces around the world then actually everybody's under threat.

43
00:05:01,553 --> 00:05:05,969
[SPEAKER_12]: The horrific events in Manchester are not the first time this nation has faced terrorism.

44
00:05:06,972 --> 00:05:10,425
[SPEAKER_12]: You and two of your senior colleagues openly supported the IRA.

45
00:05:11,328 --> 00:05:13,656
[SPEAKER_12]: How can we really trust you in stopping terrorism?

46
00:05:15,053 --> 00:05:19,037
[SPEAKER_03]: I wanted dialogue in Northern Ireland during the 1970s and 1980s.

47
00:05:19,117 --> 00:05:27,667
[SPEAKER_03]: I did make contact with Sinn Féin when they were not allowed to travel, their leadership was not allowed to travel to Britain, for example.

48
00:05:27,687 --> 00:05:29,669
[SPEAKER_03]: I wanted there to be a process.

49
00:05:30,169 --> 00:05:42,883
[SPEAKER_03]: And that peace process came about by the actions of people such as John Hume, such as Gerry Adams, such as David Trimble, who eventually brought about the ceasefires with

50
00:05:42,863 --> 00:05:47,087
[SPEAKER_03]: both governments, both the Conservative and later with the Tony Blair-led Labour government.

51
00:05:47,107 --> 00:05:55,436
[SPEAKER_03]: And that brought about the Good Friday Agreement, which respects all the historical traditions of Ireland, which is obviously fundamental to bringing about peace.

52
00:05:55,776 --> 00:06:01,502
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think we should all be pleased that we've achieved a great deal through the Good Friday Agreement.

53
00:06:01,522 --> 00:06:02,123
[SPEAKER_03]: And do you know what?

54
00:06:02,543 --> 00:06:11,993
[SPEAKER_03]: That Good Friday process, recognising those differences, has become a bit of a model for peace processes around the world, where people who were

55
00:06:12,867 --> 00:06:23,609
[SPEAKER_03]: not talking to each other, worse than that, now travel the world together in order to promote peace and dialogue in the Middle East, in Colombia and in the past in South Africa.

56
00:06:23,629 --> 00:06:25,733
[SPEAKER_03]: I think we should be pleased about those achievements.

57
00:06:25,753 --> 00:06:29,380
[SPEAKER_05]: Is it worth clarifying for Callum, did you vote for the Good Friday Agreement?

58
00:06:29,561 --> 00:06:30,302
[SPEAKER_05]: Yes I did.

59
00:06:30,856 --> 00:06:32,540
[SPEAKER_05]: Absolutely.

60
00:06:33,322 --> 00:06:34,586
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's talk about something.

61
00:06:34,967 --> 00:06:37,794
[SPEAKER_05]: Callum talks about can we trust you on stopping terrorist threats.

62
00:06:37,814 --> 00:06:38,917
[SPEAKER_05]: Let's talk about something practical.

63
00:06:39,478 --> 00:06:40,441
[SPEAKER_05]: Armed police officers.

64
00:06:40,922 --> 00:06:42,787
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you think there should be fewer?

65
00:06:42,887 --> 00:06:44,471
[SPEAKER_05]: Do you think there should be more?

66
00:06:44,672 --> 00:06:45,053
[SPEAKER_05]: The same?

67
00:06:45,334 --> 00:06:45,895
[SPEAKER_03]: None?

68
00:06:45,875 --> 00:06:51,181
[SPEAKER_03]: I think there should be what is necessary in order to save and protect life.

69
00:06:51,762 --> 00:06:54,105
[SPEAKER_03]: I want to live in a society that is safe and secure.

70
00:06:54,505 --> 00:06:57,308
[SPEAKER_03]: Ideally, nobody wants to see armed police officers anywhere.

71
00:06:57,649 --> 00:07:01,734
[SPEAKER_03]: The reality is, at the moment, they are there, and they have been necessary.

72
00:07:01,754 --> 00:07:03,095
[SPEAKER_03]: Just a quick comment, Callum.

73
00:07:03,115 --> 00:07:06,059
[SPEAKER_12]: With all due respect, Mr Corbyn, you didn't actually answer my question.

74
00:07:07,260 --> 00:07:09,703
[SPEAKER_12]: You have openly supported the IRA in the past.

75
00:07:10,163 --> 00:07:11,205
[SPEAKER_12]: And I can give you an example.

76
00:07:11,886 --> 00:07:15,730
[SPEAKER_12]: Attending a commemoration for the eight IRA men who were killed at Lochgoll,

77
00:07:16,857 --> 00:07:19,922
[SPEAKER_12]: Now, in your words, it was to honour them.

78
00:07:19,942 --> 00:07:23,569
[SPEAKER_12]: Maybe you can share with the electorate why those IRA men were actually killed.

79
00:07:24,310 --> 00:07:32,345
[SPEAKER_03]: The commemoration I think you're referring to was a meeting I was at in London where there was a period of silence for everyone who had died in Northern Ireland.

80
00:07:34,008 --> 00:07:37,093
[SPEAKER_12]: Mr Corbyn, the event was actually to commemorate

81
00:07:37,985 --> 00:07:39,387
[SPEAKER_12]: The people who were killed in Lough Gale.

82
00:07:39,767 --> 00:07:45,553
[SPEAKER_12]: The reason they were killed in Lough Gale was they were on their way to kill British policemen.

83
00:07:45,714 --> 00:07:52,401
[SPEAKER_03]: The contribution I made to that meeting was to call for a peace and dialogue process in Northern Ireland.

84
00:07:52,801 --> 00:08:07,738
[SPEAKER_03]: It's only by dialogue and process we brought about the peace in Northern Ireland and I think that is a good thing and I think going forward we need to make sure that in the Brexit negotiations there is no return to any kind of hard border between Northern Ireland and the Republic.

85
00:08:07,718 --> 00:08:08,980
[SPEAKER_05]: OK, thank you, Callum.

86
00:08:09,000 --> 00:08:09,501
[SPEAKER_05]: John Dare.

87
00:08:10,082 --> 00:08:10,302
[SPEAKER_05]: John.

88
00:08:10,903 --> 00:08:15,450
[SPEAKER_02]: Mr Corbyn, like many voters, I approve of many of the policies in your manifesto.

89
00:08:15,470 --> 00:08:20,578
[SPEAKER_02]: The problem I have is that I don't see you as someone who could effectively run this country.

90
00:08:21,039 --> 00:08:23,803
[SPEAKER_02]: How can you convince me that you're the man for the job?

91
00:08:24,526 --> 00:08:40,752
[SPEAKER_03]: We wrote this manifesto, which I'm glad you approve of, by consensus within the Labour Party and our affiliated groups and organisations and from the contribution of hundreds of non-affiliated political groups who have very important views to communicate to us.

92
00:08:41,613 --> 00:08:43,817
[SPEAKER_03]: We put those forward.

93
00:08:44,540 --> 00:08:46,803
[SPEAKER_03]: In government, we will carry this manifesto out.

94
00:08:46,903 --> 00:08:49,587
[SPEAKER_03]: This manifesto is about investing in our future.

95
00:08:49,707 --> 00:09:03,527
[SPEAKER_03]: It is about investing in our young people for the future, so that we don't have supersized classrooms, we don't have massive waiting lists in hospitals, we don't have a million people waiting for social care, we don't have thousands of people sleeping on our streets.

96
00:09:03,988 --> 00:09:05,510
[SPEAKER_03]: The choice is quite clearly there.

97
00:09:05,750 --> 00:09:11,138
[SPEAKER_03]: This manifesto, investing for the future, taxing more, a bit,

98
00:09:11,118 --> 00:09:28,596
[SPEAKER_03]: for corporation tax and for the very wealthiest, 95% will pay no more, or you can go down the road of continuing austerity, continuing cuts in all areas of public expenditure and an ever-widening gap between the richest and the poorest in our society.

99
00:09:29,117 --> 00:09:38,307
[SPEAKER_03]: I am very proud of this manifesto, proud to lead this party, and you know what, I'll be very proud to put this manifesto into action by legislation and by government.

100
00:09:38,867 --> 00:09:40,669
[SPEAKER_03]: And I'm looking forward to the chance of doing it.

101
00:09:41,577 --> 00:09:48,670
[SPEAKER_05]: Mr Corbyn, John's question was actually, he likes the manifesto, but it was your own leadership he was questioning.

102
00:09:48,690 --> 00:09:49,671
[SPEAKER_05]: Could you just address that to John Corbyn?

103
00:09:49,691 --> 00:09:54,300
[SPEAKER_03]: Well I'm sure when John and I get to know each other we'll get along fine and we'll get to like each other, I'm sure we will.

104
00:09:54,760 --> 00:09:58,868
[SPEAKER_03]: John, people have perceptions about each other, but do you know what?

105
00:09:58,968 --> 00:10:00,210
[SPEAKER_03]: In life,

106
00:10:00,190 --> 00:10:01,752
[SPEAKER_03]: I meet lots of people.

107
00:10:02,293 --> 00:10:06,539
[SPEAKER_03]: Some I agree with, some I disagree with, some I profoundly disagree with.

108
00:10:06,900 --> 00:10:08,763
[SPEAKER_03]: But I always want to get to know them.

109
00:10:09,163 --> 00:10:13,009
[SPEAKER_03]: Because everybody I meet, and everybody you meet, knows something we don't know.

110
00:10:13,069 --> 00:10:20,220
[SPEAKER_03]: You should never be so high and mighty you can't listen to somebody else and learn something from them.

111
00:10:20,480 --> 00:10:24,466
[SPEAKER_03]: To me, leadership is as much about using this as using this.

112
00:10:28,653 --> 00:10:28,893
[SPEAKER_05]: OK, Roxanne.

113
00:10:28,913 --> 00:10:29,334
[SPEAKER_05]: Moving on to Roxanne.

114
00:10:29,354 --> 00:10:29,674
[SPEAKER_05]: Where's Roxanne?

115
00:10:30,295 --> 00:10:43,070
[SPEAKER_08]: Hi Mr Colin, I'd like to know for people like myself who voted to leave the European Union and have voted Labour in the past, how are you planning to deal with immigration?

116
00:10:43,110 --> 00:10:46,274
[SPEAKER_08]: The Conservatives have pledged a number, why won't you?

117
00:10:46,334 --> 00:10:57,147
[SPEAKER_03]: When we leave the European Union we accept the results of the referendum, it's taken place, it's happened, we accept it.

118
00:10:57,751 --> 00:11:04,847
[SPEAKER_03]: The priority has to be negotiating tariff-free trade access to the European market to protect jobs in this country.

119
00:11:05,428 --> 00:11:06,169
[SPEAKER_03]: That we will do.

120
00:11:06,230 --> 00:11:11,742
[SPEAKER_03]: It also has to be about the future relationship with Europe because they are, after all, our very close neighbours.

121
00:11:12,503 --> 00:11:16,452
[SPEAKER_03]: On the issue you mentioned of immigration, the free movement

122
00:11:16,432 --> 00:11:21,823
[SPEAKER_03]: is implicit in membership of the European Union, it obviously stops when we leave the European Union.

123
00:11:22,324 --> 00:11:33,506
[SPEAKER_03]: In the future, there has to be managed migration and it has to be based on the needs of this country and our economy and of the rights of family reunion.

124
00:11:33,727 --> 00:11:36,432
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not going to stand here and put a figure

125
00:11:36,698 --> 00:11:41,709
[SPEAKER_03]: Our Prime Minister has done that now in the third election running and has got nowhere near meeting that figure.

126
00:11:42,270 --> 00:11:54,838
[SPEAKER_03]: I would say we have to have managed migration, we have to have protection of EU nationals living here just as much as there should be protection of British nationals of which there are very many living in other parts of Europe.

127
00:11:54,858 --> 00:11:56,462
[SPEAKER_03]: But we should also remember

128
00:11:56,729 --> 00:12:04,717
[SPEAKER_03]: And if people hadn't migrated to this country, we would have a much worse health service, education system, and transport system than we have.

129
00:12:04,978 --> 00:12:09,663
[SPEAKER_03]: The contribution that's made to your living standards and mine by people who have come here is huge.

130
00:12:09,883 --> 00:12:11,104
[SPEAKER_03]: But I'll tell you what will change.

131
00:12:11,405 --> 00:12:25,099
[SPEAKER_03]: We will not allow companies to bring in whole groups of very low-paid workers in order to undercut often fairly low-paid workers in this country, thus destroying their working conditions.

132
00:12:25,079 --> 00:12:28,888
[SPEAKER_03]: And so that is part of that managed process.

133
00:12:28,968 --> 00:12:34,440
[SPEAKER_03]: At the moment we have some disgraceful undercutting and we have huge impacts on different communities.

134
00:12:34,681 --> 00:12:40,253
[SPEAKER_03]: The other point I just make in finality on this, go and see Faisal's moving his hands, is that

135
00:12:40,402 --> 00:12:53,553
[SPEAKER_03]: We would also reinstate something that Gordon Brown introduced when he was Prime Minister, which was an impact fund for communities that had had an influx of new residents and needed support on vital local services.

136
00:12:53,814 --> 00:12:55,879
[SPEAKER_03]: And so we accept the result.

137
00:12:55,859 --> 00:13:00,948
[SPEAKER_03]: We negotiate with Europe, we have a good relationship with Europe, and we manage our own future.

138
00:13:01,028 --> 00:13:06,377
[SPEAKER_05]: To just help Roxanne out here, you won't give a number, but the current net figure is £248,000.

139
00:13:07,038 --> 00:13:07,318
[SPEAKER_05]: Higher?

140
00:13:07,539 --> 00:13:07,839
[SPEAKER_05]: Lower?

141
00:13:07,859 --> 00:13:09,061
[SPEAKER_05]: The same?

142
00:13:09,722 --> 00:13:14,831
[SPEAKER_03]: I would have thought, under a managed migration system, it certainly wouldn't go up any more.

143
00:13:14,851 --> 00:13:15,572
[SPEAKER_03]: It would probably

144
00:13:15,552 --> 00:13:31,633
[SPEAKER_03]: probably, but I don't want to be held to this, come down, that's a probability, but I would say we have to recognise that we do have serious skill shortages in this country because we have not invested enough in education and training for a very long time in this country.

145
00:13:31,673 --> 00:13:36,700
[SPEAKER_03]: We need to turn that around.

146
00:13:37,608 --> 00:13:39,010
[SPEAKER_14]: Hi, hello.

147
00:13:39,411 --> 00:13:41,134
[SPEAKER_14]: Hi Miranda, how are you doing?

148
00:13:41,154 --> 00:13:46,843
[SPEAKER_14]: By contrast, I'm a Remain voter and I feel that the Labour response to Brexit has been lacklustre.

149
00:13:47,724 --> 00:13:53,573
[SPEAKER_14]: I don't really see a big difference between the Tory and Labour responses, but it's a really big issue for me.

150
00:13:54,415 --> 00:13:59,042
[SPEAKER_14]: Can you tell me why I should vote Labour instead of Lib Dem as part of the 48%?

151
00:13:59,630 --> 00:14:04,336
[SPEAKER_03]: because we have to accept the reality of the result of the referendum.

152
00:14:04,876 --> 00:14:05,417
[SPEAKER_03]: It happened.

153
00:14:05,477 --> 00:14:06,759
[SPEAKER_03]: It was a democratic choice.

154
00:14:07,159 --> 00:14:11,344
[SPEAKER_03]: More people voted in that than any other recorded vote in our history.

155
00:14:11,645 --> 00:14:12,886
[SPEAKER_03]: And so it's there.

156
00:14:12,906 --> 00:14:13,487
[SPEAKER_03]: It's a decision.

157
00:14:14,328 --> 00:14:17,171
[SPEAKER_03]: That doesn't mean we're leaving the European Union.

158
00:14:17,191 --> 00:14:19,674
[SPEAKER_03]: It doesn't mean we're leaving Europe as a continent.

159
00:14:19,694 --> 00:14:22,758
[SPEAKER_03]: It's still there, obviously, and we're going to have to have a relationship with it.

160
00:14:23,239 --> 00:14:27,544
[SPEAKER_03]: I've said, in answer to our friend over there, I said that

161
00:14:27,524 --> 00:14:32,070
[SPEAKER_03]: We would guarantee the rights of European Union nationals in Britain to remain here.

162
00:14:32,310 --> 00:14:38,799
[SPEAKER_03]: And indeed, within days of the referendum, Andy Burnham, who was then our shadow Home Secretary, proposed that resolution in the House of Commons.

163
00:14:38,819 --> 00:14:44,366
[SPEAKER_03]: And it was, in fact, carried by a huge majority, because the Conservatives chose not to take part.

164
00:14:44,786 --> 00:14:46,769
[SPEAKER_03]: There's going to be a relationship with Europe.

165
00:14:47,129 --> 00:14:50,333
[SPEAKER_03]: Our universities must have a close relationship with Europe.

166
00:14:50,634 --> 00:14:56,181
[SPEAKER_03]: We will defend working rights, such as working time directive, paternal leave, maternity leave.

167
00:14:56,161 --> 00:14:59,485
[SPEAKER_03]: all those very important things we've gained from the European Union.

168
00:14:59,666 --> 00:15:11,081
[SPEAKER_03]: We'll protect those in the future and we will also remain part of a number of very important agencies such as policing and intelligence sharing as well as environmental protocols.

169
00:15:11,181 --> 00:15:15,747
[SPEAKER_03]: It's no good one side of a sea polluting it and the other side not.

170
00:15:15,787 --> 00:15:17,950
[SPEAKER_03]: You've both got to agree not to pollute the sea.

171
00:15:17,970 --> 00:15:19,973
[SPEAKER_03]: You have to work together to achieve things.

172
00:15:19,993 --> 00:15:21,595
[SPEAKER_03]: So what I say to you is

173
00:15:22,216 --> 00:15:23,157
[SPEAKER_03]: The result is there.

174
00:15:23,197 --> 00:15:24,039
[SPEAKER_03]: It happened.

175
00:15:24,780 --> 00:15:29,407
[SPEAKER_03]: Let's build a sensible, good, tariff-free trade relationship with Europe.

176
00:15:29,427 --> 00:15:36,377
[SPEAKER_03]: Every car that's made in Britain or made, most of the cars that are made in Germany, the parts come from both sides of the channel.

177
00:15:36,577 --> 00:15:38,019
[SPEAKER_03]: You could say the same with aircraft.

178
00:15:38,200 --> 00:15:41,404
[SPEAKER_03]: You could say the same with an awful lot of other manufacturing industry.

179
00:15:41,745 --> 00:15:43,888
[SPEAKER_03]: That's going to carry on, and it will have to carry on.

180
00:15:44,168 --> 00:15:46,852
[SPEAKER_03]: Otherwise, we'll destroy our own manufacturing industry.

181
00:15:46,872 --> 00:15:48,595
[SPEAKER_03]: But I'll tell you what we won't do.

182
00:15:48,575 --> 00:15:56,865
[SPEAKER_03]: We won't threaten Europe with turning this country into a sort of corporate tax haven with low tax, low wages and low investment.

183
00:15:57,145 --> 00:16:12,203
[SPEAKER_03]: We want high wage, high investment, growing economy with good relations with our neighbours and indeed of course with the rest of the world.

184
00:16:12,571 --> 00:16:20,899
[SPEAKER_13]: I'm a proud Mancunian and a small business owner brought up in a Labour voting household by salt-of-the-earth parents who've gave me their best.

185
00:16:22,080 --> 00:16:41,278
[SPEAKER_13]: Why have you made it impossible for me to vote Labour in this election with your ruthless, short-sighted policies such as 26% corporation tax, the abolishment of zero-hour contracts, £10 an hour minimum wage, and now you want to put VAT on my children's school fees?

186
00:16:48,413 --> 00:16:51,357
[SPEAKER_03]: Corporation tax was 28% in 2010.

187
00:16:51,998 --> 00:16:56,885
[SPEAKER_03]: This government has reduced it and proposes to reduce it further.

188
00:16:57,826 --> 00:16:59,709
[SPEAKER_03]: We're going to put it back up to 26%.

189
00:17:01,051 --> 00:17:01,832
[SPEAKER_03]: And why are we doing that?

190
00:17:02,613 --> 00:17:08,001
[SPEAKER_03]: Because this country is badly divided between the richest and the poorest.

191
00:17:08,622 --> 00:17:14,069
[SPEAKER_03]: You put corporate tax and tax at the top end down, the division gets greater.

192
00:17:14,570 --> 00:17:15,872
[SPEAKER_03]: Are you happy

193
00:17:15,852 --> 00:17:23,022
[SPEAKER_03]: that so many of our children are going to school with supersized classes, so many of our children are going to school hungry.

194
00:17:23,502 --> 00:17:29,670
[SPEAKER_03]: Are you happy with so many people waiting for hospital operations, a million waiting for social care?

195
00:17:30,411 --> 00:17:33,375
[SPEAKER_03]: You don't address these problems by ignoring them.

196
00:17:33,816 --> 00:17:42,147
[SPEAKER_03]: I appeal to you, as obviously a traditional person who supported our party, recognise that we're all better off

197
00:17:42,970 --> 00:17:44,512
[SPEAKER_03]: when everybody is better off.

198
00:17:45,013 --> 00:17:49,078
[SPEAKER_03]: And your children want to get a home of their own in the future.

199
00:17:49,478 --> 00:17:54,084
[SPEAKER_03]: If we build the homes for them, both to rent as well as to buy, then they've got a better chance.

200
00:17:54,525 --> 00:17:57,488
[SPEAKER_03]: Your children, I'm sure, would like to go to university.

201
00:17:57,889 --> 00:18:06,520
[SPEAKER_03]: I do not believe we should charge fees for our students to go to universities because we all benefit from them graduating and becoming well-qualified citizens.

202
00:18:06,760 --> 00:18:10,024
[SPEAKER_03]: So what we're proposing in this manifesto is

203
00:18:10,004 --> 00:18:20,645
[SPEAKER_03]: transformational because for the first time for many years we're saying this younger generation should not be worse off than we are or ones that went before.

204
00:18:20,806 --> 00:18:22,108
[SPEAKER_03]: They should actually be better off.

205
00:18:22,168 --> 00:18:25,215
[SPEAKER_03]: This is about rejigging the way that we run our economy.

206
00:18:25,375 --> 00:18:28,401
[SPEAKER_03]: But I also say to anyone running a small business

207
00:18:29,613 --> 00:18:34,041
[SPEAKER_03]: I work with small businesses, I talk to them, I listen very carefully to what they have to say.

208
00:18:34,242 --> 00:18:41,796
[SPEAKER_03]: They are often very badly exploited by much bigger business who delay on payments, often don't pay at all and force them out of business.

209
00:18:42,036 --> 00:18:49,591
[SPEAKER_03]: We want a society and an economy that invests and a legal system that protects those that are working really hard.

210
00:18:49,951 --> 00:18:51,975
[SPEAKER_03]: Surely a £10 an hour

211
00:18:51,955 --> 00:19:03,765
[SPEAKER_03]: minimum wage, a living wage, a real living wage by 2020 would mean we actually spend probably a bit less on working tax credits, but it would also make an awful lot of people a lot better off.

212
00:19:03,825 --> 00:19:04,266
[SPEAKER_03]: And do you know what?

213
00:19:04,406 --> 00:19:06,467
[SPEAKER_03]: They'd spend the money in the local economy.

214
00:19:06,568 --> 00:19:08,890
[SPEAKER_03]: It would be something that would be good for all of us.

215
00:19:09,130 --> 00:19:10,671
[SPEAKER_03]: I appeal to you, think again.

216
00:19:11,071 --> 00:19:13,193
[SPEAKER_03]: How did we get our welfare state in Britain?

217
00:19:13,413 --> 00:19:15,095
[SPEAKER_03]: How do we get our National Health Service?

218
00:19:15,115 --> 00:19:21,000
[SPEAKER_03]: We got it because the Labour Party was bold enough in the post-war period to invest in the future.

219
00:19:20,980 --> 00:19:22,662
[SPEAKER_03]: Our Labour government will do the same.

220
00:19:22,782 --> 00:19:29,450
[SPEAKER_05]: We're just trying to get one more... David Gerrard.

221
00:19:29,470 --> 00:19:29,891
[SPEAKER_16]: David, please, David.

222
00:19:29,911 --> 00:19:29,971
Hi.

223
00:19:29,991 --> 00:19:30,171
[SPEAKER_16]: This way.

224
00:19:30,191 --> 00:19:36,599
[SPEAKER_16]: Given your long-standing support for nuclear disarmament, would you be prepared to use the nuclear deterrent, and if so, in what circumstances?

225
00:19:38,301 --> 00:19:42,786
[SPEAKER_03]: I want to live in a world that's free of the danger of a nuclear holocaust.

226
00:19:43,487 --> 00:19:47,832
[SPEAKER_03]: Any nuclear weapon used anywhere in the world is a disaster for all of us.

227
00:19:47,930 --> 00:19:58,671
[SPEAKER_03]: And I've spent my life working with peace organisations, working with the United Nations over the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty in order to bring about global disarmament.

228
00:19:59,172 --> 00:20:05,044
[SPEAKER_03]: I would see my responsibility as our Prime Minister to contribute to a world of peace in the future.

229
00:20:05,227 --> 00:20:22,769
[SPEAKER_03]: That means being very serious about the dangers, very serious about promoting what China is trying to achieve in Korea with the six-party talks, be very serious in what President Obama achieved with his agreement with Iran, but also look at the other threats that we face as well.

230
00:20:23,309 --> 00:20:25,051
[SPEAKER_03]: Cyber attacks are very serious.

231
00:20:25,232 --> 00:20:30,458
[SPEAKER_03]: We saw that with the attack on our National Health Service only a couple of weeks ago.

232
00:20:30,438 --> 00:20:34,990
[SPEAKER_03]: Random acts of terror, such as we saw in Manchester, are a real threat as well.

233
00:20:35,631 --> 00:20:42,950
[SPEAKER_03]: We have to defend our way of life, our society and our country, by an intelligent engagement with the rest of the world.

234
00:20:43,552 --> 00:20:47,502
[SPEAKER_03]: And I want to bring about our contribution to a more peaceful world.

235
00:20:47,482 --> 00:20:57,414
[SPEAKER_05]: Can I just keep to the practical implication of David's question, which is in 11 days' time you could be Prime Minister and you would have to write those letters of last resort to the Trident submarine commanders.

236
00:20:57,514 --> 00:20:58,315
[SPEAKER_05]: Are you going to write those letters?

237
00:20:58,335 --> 00:21:05,323
[SPEAKER_03]: I will write the appropriate letter to our commanders, who are obviously very responsible, very loyal naval officers.

238
00:21:06,024 --> 00:21:10,830
[SPEAKER_05]: OK. Well, that brings us to the end of our first question and answer session of the evening.

239
00:21:10,890 --> 00:21:12,212
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much, Mr Corbyn.

240
00:21:15,235 --> 00:21:15,435
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

241
00:21:15,455 --> 00:21:15,936
[SPEAKER_05]: And thank you very much.

242
00:21:20,843 --> 00:21:47,880
[SPEAKER_05]: Coming next, Mr. Corbyn, head-to-head with Jeremy Paxman.

243
00:21:55,319 --> 00:21:59,024
[SPEAKER_06]: Jeremy Corbyn, in 11 days' time you might be Prime Minister.

244
00:21:59,164 --> 00:22:01,467
[SPEAKER_06]: People are entitled to know about you, aren't they?

245
00:22:01,788 --> 00:22:02,829
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

246
00:22:03,169 --> 00:22:04,491
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm looking forward to it as well.

247
00:22:04,631 --> 00:22:04,872
[SPEAKER_06]: Good.

248
00:22:05,593 --> 00:22:12,402
[SPEAKER_06]: Are you frustrated that so many of your core ideas, your basic principles, didn't make it into this manifesto?

249
00:22:12,922 --> 00:22:14,324
[SPEAKER_06]: Oh, come on, this is a really good matter.

250
00:22:14,344 --> 00:22:15,446
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm glad you got it, by the way.

251
00:22:15,846 --> 00:22:16,728
[SPEAKER_06]: It's a really good...

252
00:22:16,748 --> 00:22:18,610
[SPEAKER_06]: I've had to read it, too.

253
00:22:18,590 --> 00:22:19,972
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, I helped to write it.

254
00:22:20,673 --> 00:22:23,698
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah, but it doesn't include key things that you believe in, does it?

255
00:22:23,718 --> 00:22:34,994
[SPEAKER_03]: Listen, this manifesto is a product of the views of the Labour Party, of party conference decisions, and of the views put forward by individuals in the Shadow Cabinet.

256
00:22:35,014 --> 00:22:39,801
[SPEAKER_06]: But this manifesto fundamentally... You couldn't persuade the Cabinet, the Shadow Cabinet... Can I finish this?

257
00:22:39,962 --> 00:22:40,262
[SPEAKER_06]: No.

258
00:22:40,542 --> 00:22:42,085
[SPEAKER_06]: Oh, come on.

259
00:22:42,345 --> 00:22:47,753
[SPEAKER_06]: Couldn't persuade the Shadow Cabinet to accept your basic principle

260
00:22:47,733 --> 00:22:51,111
[SPEAKER_06]: which you have adhered to for the whole of your adult life.

261
00:22:51,327 --> 00:22:52,969
[SPEAKER_06]: that there should be nuclear disarmament.

262
00:22:52,989 --> 00:22:55,592
[SPEAKER_06]: You're promising this to renew Trident.

263
00:22:55,612 --> 00:23:03,621
[SPEAKER_03]: It was a conference decision by the Labour Party, and as the leader of the party, I accept the democracy of our party.

264
00:23:03,902 --> 00:23:05,043
[SPEAKER_03]: Is that morally right?

265
00:23:05,463 --> 00:23:16,156
[SPEAKER_03]: In answer to the questions put earlier, I made the point that as Prime Minister, I will do all I can to bring about a nuclear-free world because I'm horrified at the very idea.

266
00:23:16,816 --> 00:23:19,039
[SPEAKER_03]: You promised to renew.

267
00:23:19,019 --> 00:23:20,401
[SPEAKER_03]: of a nuclear attack.

268
00:23:20,421 --> 00:23:21,883
[SPEAKER_03]: He promised to win you a nuclear weapon.

269
00:23:22,384 --> 00:23:23,926
[SPEAKER_03]: Is that morally right?

270
00:23:24,647 --> 00:23:28,112
[SPEAKER_03]: Listen, it's there in our manifesto because our conference voted for it.

271
00:23:28,412 --> 00:23:30,075
[SPEAKER_03]: I have to accept that decision.

272
00:23:30,095 --> 00:23:30,996
[SPEAKER_03]: Do you think it's morally right?

273
00:23:31,016 --> 00:23:31,457
[SPEAKER_03]: Can I finish?

274
00:23:32,078 --> 00:23:32,538
[SPEAKER_03]: Can I finish?

275
00:23:32,799 --> 00:23:33,600
[SPEAKER_03]: What I want to see...

276
00:23:33,620 --> 00:23:36,364
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm asking you perfectly simply, do you think it's morally right?

277
00:23:36,384 --> 00:23:39,408
[SPEAKER_03]: What I want to see is a nuclear-free world.

278
00:23:39,869 --> 00:23:41,591
[SPEAKER_03]: Of course everybody wants to see that.

279
00:23:42,012 --> 00:23:43,233
[SPEAKER_03]: But is it morally right?

280
00:23:43,434 --> 00:23:44,335
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not so sure about that.

281
00:23:44,315 --> 00:23:45,176
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not so sure about that.

282
00:23:45,196 --> 00:23:48,539
[SPEAKER_03]: If that's what you believe, is it morally right to renew a nuclear deterrent?

283
00:23:48,559 --> 00:23:50,380
[SPEAKER_03]: That is the decision that's been taken.

284
00:23:50,560 --> 00:23:53,823
[SPEAKER_03]: We will work for a nuclear-free world.

285
00:23:53,843 --> 00:23:54,364
[SPEAKER_03]: I note you don't answer.

286
00:23:54,384 --> 00:23:58,928
[SPEAKER_03]: We will work through the Nuclear Non-Proliferation Treaty to achieve that.

287
00:23:58,968 --> 00:24:01,310
[SPEAKER_03]: That surely is something well worth doing.

288
00:24:02,251 --> 00:24:06,154
[SPEAKER_06]: A number of your other core beliefs do make it into this manifesto, don't they?

289
00:24:06,174 --> 00:24:11,318
[SPEAKER_06]: About nationalising the Royal Mail, for example, or the railways, or energy companies, or water companies.

290
00:24:11,799 --> 00:24:13,140
[SPEAKER_06]: Why not banks?

291
00:24:13,525 --> 00:24:16,289
[SPEAKER_06]: Some of our banks aren't publicly owned, as it is, actually.

292
00:24:16,309 --> 00:24:21,778
[SPEAKER_06]: You said you have always believed that banks should be publicly owned.

293
00:24:22,298 --> 00:24:25,283
[SPEAKER_03]: There are some banks that are publicly owned.

294
00:24:25,443 --> 00:24:36,761
[SPEAKER_03]: We will be promoting building societies, cooperatives, and we will be promoting a national investment bank, which won't be a lending bank, it will be an investment bank.

295
00:24:37,021 --> 00:24:38,423
[SPEAKER_03]: And that is an important part of it.

296
00:24:38,463 --> 00:24:40,326
[SPEAKER_03]: You believe in public ownership of retail banks?

297
00:24:40,306 --> 00:24:45,613
[SPEAKER_03]: an important part of directing investment in this country.

298
00:24:45,974 --> 00:24:50,200
[SPEAKER_03]: Of the retail banks, RBS is largely publicly owned.

299
00:24:50,220 --> 00:24:52,583
[SPEAKER_03]: There is a public stake in most of the banks.

300
00:24:52,744 --> 00:24:56,028
[SPEAKER_06]: I would always favour banks being in public ownership.

301
00:24:56,248 --> 00:24:57,430
[SPEAKER_06]: You said that in 2013.

302
00:24:57,771 --> 00:24:59,052
[SPEAKER_06]: You do.

303
00:24:59,072 --> 00:24:59,854
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, I did say that.

304
00:24:59,874 --> 00:25:02,297
[SPEAKER_03]: But it doesn't get into the manifesto, does it?

305
00:25:02,277 --> 00:25:07,845
[SPEAKER_03]: Jeremy, what we seem to be struggling with here is an understanding of a process that brings about a manifesto.

306
00:25:07,865 --> 00:25:08,025
[SPEAKER_03]: No, no.

307
00:25:08,125 --> 00:25:11,690
[SPEAKER_06]: What we're struggling here with is how much this represents what you believe.

308
00:25:11,710 --> 00:25:14,754
[SPEAKER_03]: I am not a dictator who writes things to tell people what to do.

309
00:25:14,995 --> 00:25:17,518
[SPEAKER_03]: This is a product of a process in our party.

310
00:25:17,779 --> 00:25:24,027
[SPEAKER_03]: That's why I was elected leader of our party, to give a voice to the members and those that are affiliated to our party.

311
00:25:24,047 --> 00:25:25,830
[SPEAKER_06]: All right, let's take another aspect of it.

312
00:25:27,873 --> 00:25:30,116
[SPEAKER_06]: You say you'll freeze benefits for three years.

313
00:25:31,057 --> 00:25:31,778
[SPEAKER_03]: You will?

314
00:25:32,348 --> 00:25:38,841
[SPEAKER_03]: Now what we've said is we will put two billion into the benefit system per year in order to... That's tax credits.

315
00:25:39,602 --> 00:25:48,720
[SPEAKER_03]: In order to reduce the effects we will also end the indignity of the... Will you freeze benefits for three years then?

316
00:25:49,342 --> 00:25:51,884
[SPEAKER_03]: Benefits will be paid, of course.

317
00:25:52,285 --> 00:25:55,988
[SPEAKER_03]: Benefits will be uprated, and will be uprated, of course.

318
00:25:56,749 --> 00:26:14,086
[SPEAKER_03]: And there will be a higher living wage, as I've outlined, which will of course mean that those benefits that are paid for people in work, and indeed the majority of benefits go to people in work, not out of work, will probably reduce.

319
00:26:14,106 --> 00:26:16,108
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm asking you whether they'll be frozen.

320
00:26:16,088 --> 00:26:19,573
[SPEAKER_03]: No, they're not going to be frozen because they'll be uprated every year, as they should be.

321
00:26:19,593 --> 00:26:19,914
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

322
00:26:21,436 --> 00:26:23,719
[SPEAKER_06]: What about money for the security services?

323
00:26:23,820 --> 00:26:35,477
[SPEAKER_06]: How can we take that seriously when your Shadow Chancellor was photographed holding a letter which called for the abolition of MI5, the abolition of a special branch and the disarming of the police?

324
00:26:36,198 --> 00:26:37,540
[SPEAKER_06]: We've made it very clear...

325
00:26:38,920 --> 00:26:44,047
[SPEAKER_03]: We have made it very clear that we will provide more police.

326
00:26:44,208 --> 00:26:47,452
[SPEAKER_03]: This government has taken 20,000 police officers off our streets.

327
00:26:47,632 --> 00:26:49,795
[SPEAKER_03]: But you don't deny that John Donald said all that.

328
00:26:49,816 --> 00:26:51,939
[SPEAKER_03]: We'll put 10,000 more on our streets.

329
00:26:52,279 --> 00:27:00,050
[SPEAKER_03]: We've also said quite clearly that... How can we believe that when the Shadow Chancellor believes in disbanding MI5 and the special branches?

330
00:27:00,070 --> 00:27:04,236
[SPEAKER_03]: The Shadow Chancellor is the one who signed off that pledge in the manifesto.

331
00:27:04,891 --> 00:27:07,515
[SPEAKER_06]: So he says one thing one day and one thing another day.

332
00:27:07,635 --> 00:27:11,621
[SPEAKER_03]: John McDonnell supports the need for more police officers.

333
00:27:11,821 --> 00:27:14,706
[SPEAKER_03]: Does he still believe in abolishing MI5?

334
00:27:14,726 --> 00:27:21,216
[SPEAKER_03]: John McDonnell also accepts the need for the accountability to Parliament of our security services, which is important.

335
00:27:21,656 --> 00:27:27,185
[SPEAKER_03]: But he also accepts, as I do, the need to have security services that do protect us.

336
00:27:27,285 --> 00:27:28,587
[SPEAKER_03]: Manchester is a good example.

337
00:27:28,607 --> 00:27:34,155
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think when all the inquiries have been completed in Manchester, I think we need to look at those needs.

338
00:27:34,135 --> 00:27:48,125
[SPEAKER_06]: So he signs letters which call for the abolition of MI5 and Special Branch and the rest of it, but when it comes to the manifesto, he's perfectly happy to sign off on more police officers and, doubtless, more money for MI5.

339
00:27:48,186 --> 00:27:51,132
[SPEAKER_03]: What you're going to see with John McDonnell is a Chancellor

340
00:27:51,112 --> 00:28:06,790
[SPEAKER_03]: that looks at the needs of the country, looks at the needs of the people of this country and invests in our future, not hands money away in tax relief to big corporations and at the top end of our society.

341
00:28:11,536 --> 00:28:17,143
[SPEAKER_06]: There is nothing in this manifesto about getting rid of the monarchy, which is another thing you believe in, isn't it?

342
00:28:18,644 --> 00:28:20,967
[SPEAKER_03]: Look, there's nothing in there because we're not going to do it.

343
00:28:22,162 --> 00:28:28,015
[SPEAKER_06]: But you do believe in it, don't you?

344
00:28:28,035 --> 00:28:30,360
[SPEAKER_03]: Listen, it's not on anybody's agenda.

345
00:28:30,380 --> 00:28:31,583
[SPEAKER_03]: It's certainly not on my agenda.

346
00:28:31,703 --> 00:28:32,465
[SPEAKER_03]: And do you know what?

347
00:28:32,485 --> 00:28:33,728
[SPEAKER_03]: I had a very nice chat with the Queen.

348
00:28:35,792 --> 00:28:36,835
[SPEAKER_03]: But you don't like her, do you?

349
00:28:36,855 --> 00:28:38,398
[SPEAKER_03]: You don't like what she represents.

350
00:28:39,273 --> 00:28:43,818
[SPEAKER_03]: We got along absolutely fine, perfectly fine, but I don't think she should be brought into political discussion.

351
00:28:43,978 --> 00:28:50,584
[SPEAKER_06]: Any human being anywhere can have a nice conversation with anybody, but you do not believe in the institution of monarchy, do you?

352
00:28:50,604 --> 00:28:54,348
[SPEAKER_03]: Look, I believe in a democracy, and we live in a democracy.

353
00:28:54,388 --> 00:28:59,453
[SPEAKER_03]: We have a titular head of state as the monarch, but without political power.

354
00:28:59,473 --> 00:29:03,978
[SPEAKER_06]: And when the Queen's reign comes to an end, should we call stumps on the whole thing then?

355
00:29:04,198 --> 00:29:05,179
[SPEAKER_06]: Call it a day.

356
00:29:05,851 --> 00:29:09,656
[SPEAKER_03]: Look, the law is there and that's what will prevail.

357
00:29:09,976 --> 00:29:13,681
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm fighting this election, Jeremy, on something very important.

358
00:29:13,701 --> 00:29:16,285
[SPEAKER_03]: That is the levels of poverty in our society.

359
00:29:16,525 --> 00:29:20,170
[SPEAKER_03]: The levels of children that are not supported properly in our society.

360
00:29:20,190 --> 00:29:22,092
[SPEAKER_03]: The question is how that reflects your beliefs.

361
00:29:22,233 --> 00:29:25,437
[SPEAKER_03]: Jeremy, I'm fighting this election on social justice.

362
00:29:25,717 --> 00:29:28,901
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm fighting this election to give us a stronger economy for the future.

363
00:29:29,082 --> 00:29:35,470
[SPEAKER_06]: There's a whole series of things that you couldn't even persuade your own party to put in the manifesto that you believe in.

364
00:29:35,939 --> 00:29:44,113
[SPEAKER_03]: Jeremy, this manifesto reflects what would be a profound and very good change in our society.

365
00:29:44,314 --> 00:29:50,545
[SPEAKER_03]: Because for the first time you'd have a government that was saying you cannot go on loading our students with debt.

366
00:29:50,745 --> 00:29:53,290
[SPEAKER_03]: You cannot go on overcrowding our classrooms.

367
00:29:53,310 --> 00:29:55,654
[SPEAKER_03]: You cannot go on underfunding our hospitals.

368
00:29:55,894 --> 00:30:00,883
[SPEAKER_03]: You have to invest by all of us for the future of all of us.

369
00:30:00,863 --> 00:30:03,448
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't want to live in a country of food banks.

370
00:30:03,969 --> 00:30:06,194
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't want to live in a country of homeless people.

371
00:30:06,394 --> 00:30:15,312
[SPEAKER_03]: I want to live in a country that actually does seriously care for all.

372
00:30:15,359 --> 00:30:20,487
[SPEAKER_06]: You will have to take this country into negotiations with the rest of Europe.

373
00:30:21,268 --> 00:30:28,479
[SPEAKER_06]: When they look at you and they see a man who cannot get his core beliefs into his own manifesto, are they going to take you seriously?

374
00:30:28,879 --> 00:30:31,984
[SPEAKER_03]: Listen, what they're going to take very seriously is

375
00:30:31,964 --> 00:30:43,060
[SPEAKER_03]: that we would have been elected with a mandate, a mandate to negotiate a tariff-free trade access to the European market, that we will protect European nationals living here.

376
00:30:43,340 --> 00:30:58,162
[SPEAKER_03]: What they will see is a government that is going to protect the protocols, environmental conditions, workers' rights that we achieved through Europe, and a government that wants a serious relationship with Europe but respects the result of our referendum in that we're leaving the European Union.

377
00:30:58,182 --> 00:31:01,887
[SPEAKER_03]: You are prepared to contemplate their no deal?

378
00:31:01,867 --> 00:31:02,829
[SPEAKER_06]: There's going to be a deal.

379
00:31:03,269 --> 00:31:04,471
[SPEAKER_06]: There is going to be a deal.

380
00:31:04,491 --> 00:31:05,933
[SPEAKER_06]: Would you leave Europe without a deal?

381
00:31:06,234 --> 00:31:10,621
[SPEAKER_03]: We will make sure there's a deal, and you know what, we won't start... How much of our money are you prepared to give Brussels?

382
00:31:10,641 --> 00:31:19,935
[SPEAKER_03]: We won't start the negotiations by megaphone diplomacy and threatening Europe with some kind of offshore tax haven on the shores of Europe.

383
00:31:20,216 --> 00:31:24,803
[SPEAKER_03]: We'll start those negotiations seriously, seriously, with respect to them.

384
00:31:24,783 --> 00:31:29,208
[SPEAKER_06]: How much money are you prepared to give to Brussels in order to get a deal?

385
00:31:29,288 --> 00:31:33,333
[SPEAKER_03]: Jeremy, there are going to be negotiations over all of that.

386
00:31:33,834 --> 00:31:36,737
[SPEAKER_03]: I've seen the figures that Michel Barnier has bandied around.

387
00:31:36,958 --> 00:31:38,800
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't recognise those figures.

388
00:31:39,441 --> 00:31:41,003
[SPEAKER_03]: Others may not also.

389
00:31:41,283 --> 00:31:42,525
[SPEAKER_03]: We will obviously negotiate them.

390
00:31:42,565 --> 00:31:45,268
[SPEAKER_03]: Where we have a legal obligation, it must be met.

391
00:31:45,588 --> 00:31:48,251
[SPEAKER_03]: Where the EU has a legal obligation, it must be met.

392
00:31:48,632 --> 00:31:50,034
[SPEAKER_03]: But we have to recognise...

393
00:31:50,054 --> 00:31:51,195
[SPEAKER_03]: So you've done some sums?

394
00:31:51,175 --> 00:31:58,050
[SPEAKER_03]: We have to recognise that we're leaving the European Union.

395
00:31:58,091 --> 00:32:05,287
[SPEAKER_03]: The priority has to be tariff-free trade access because we have a lot of manufacturing industry... Haven't you done any sums?

396
00:32:05,547 --> 00:32:06,389
[SPEAKER_03]: Can I finish, please?

397
00:32:06,690 --> 00:32:06,971
[SPEAKER_03]: Really?

398
00:32:07,251 --> 00:32:08,053
[SPEAKER_03]: Just for a second?

399
00:32:08,084 --> 00:32:09,787
[SPEAKER_06]: No, I'm asking you for a figure.

400
00:32:10,028 --> 00:32:12,773
[SPEAKER_03]: How much are you prepared to give to get a deal?

401
00:32:12,933 --> 00:32:18,104
[SPEAKER_03]: Jeremy, I'm trying to explain the basis on which we propose to negotiate.

402
00:32:18,224 --> 00:32:19,887
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm asking you a very simple question.

403
00:32:20,268 --> 00:32:22,192
[SPEAKER_06]: How much are you prepared to pay to get a deal?

404
00:32:22,212 --> 00:32:22,953
[SPEAKER_06]: And you know what?

405
00:32:23,153 --> 00:32:27,782
[SPEAKER_03]: There is no answer to your question because nobody could answer at this stage what I've said.

406
00:32:27,802 --> 00:32:28,624
[SPEAKER_03]: Well, you don't know.

407
00:32:29,380 --> 00:32:34,709
[SPEAKER_03]: I've said what we would do is pay that we are legally required to do.

408
00:32:35,390 --> 00:32:38,275
[SPEAKER_03]: There will have to be an agreement on trade access.

409
00:32:38,315 --> 00:32:51,777
[SPEAKER_03]: Now, it's not a one-way street because all of our manufacturing industry relies on supply chains across Europe, as indeed many European manufacturers supply chains from this side of the channel as well.

410
00:32:51,757 --> 00:32:57,565
[SPEAKER_06]: Would a Corbyn Brexit mean lower immigration to this country from outside the EU?

411
00:32:57,585 --> 00:33:00,228
[SPEAKER_03]: We had that discussion with the audience earlier on.

412
00:33:01,309 --> 00:33:02,711
[SPEAKER_03]: Free movement... You said probably.

413
00:33:03,152 --> 00:33:06,736
[SPEAKER_03]: Free movement ends when we leave the European Union.

414
00:33:07,578 --> 00:33:08,719
[SPEAKER_03]: We will, as I've said...

415
00:33:08,739 --> 00:33:11,262
[SPEAKER_06]: So you're not giving any guarantee on immigration?

416
00:33:11,282 --> 00:33:19,173
[SPEAKER_03]: I've said we'll protect the rights of EU nationals here and we want the same for British nationals across Europe because these are people, they're families...

417
00:33:19,193 --> 00:33:21,055
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm asking you about immigration.

418
00:33:21,035 --> 00:33:27,069
[SPEAKER_03]: Yeah, and we will stop the undercutting that goes on by importation of low paid workers.

419
00:33:27,109 --> 00:33:32,742
[SPEAKER_03]: There will be migration of managers necessary to sustain our economy.

420
00:33:32,782 --> 00:33:34,826
[SPEAKER_03]: I'm not going to sit here and make promises.

421
00:33:35,067 --> 00:33:39,938
[SPEAKER_03]: Theresa May has done that for the third election running and hasn't got anywhere near meeting her promises in the last two

422
00:33:39,918 --> 00:33:43,322
[SPEAKER_06]: So you're not making any promise about whether you would reduce immigration?

423
00:33:43,342 --> 00:33:48,167
[SPEAKER_03]: I suspect it would probably be slightly less or less, but...

424
00:33:48,367 --> 00:33:50,249
[SPEAKER_03]: Probably is hardly a commitment, is it?

425
00:33:50,269 --> 00:33:52,171
[SPEAKER_06]: Do you think there are too many immigrants in this country?

426
00:33:52,191 --> 00:33:57,757
[SPEAKER_03]: Listen, we require migrant workers to maintain our health service and much of our industry.

427
00:33:57,978 --> 00:34:03,544
[SPEAKER_03]: We have a skills gap because we haven't invested enough in skills training.

428
00:34:03,564 --> 00:34:05,706
[SPEAKER_06]: Let's look at the security of the state, then.

429
00:34:06,547 --> 00:34:12,722
[SPEAKER_06]: The primary duty of a prime minister, the overwhelming duty, is the protection of the state.

430
00:34:14,306 --> 00:34:20,761
[SPEAKER_06]: And yet the only time in recent history that there has been an invasion of British soil was the invasion of the Falklands.

431
00:34:21,724 --> 00:34:24,370
[SPEAKER_06]: And you recall what you said then, don't you?

432
00:34:25,565 --> 00:34:34,723
[SPEAKER_03]: I wanted there to be a UN-brokered plan of a ceasefire at that time, which President Terry of Peru was trying to pursue.

433
00:34:34,783 --> 00:34:43,860
[SPEAKER_06]: You said that young unemployed men were being sent to the South Atlantic to die in pursuit of a Tory plot.

434
00:34:45,275 --> 00:34:48,339
[SPEAKER_03]: What I wanted was a stopping of that war.

435
00:34:48,500 --> 00:34:53,427
[SPEAKER_03]: I didn't want any young men, British or Argentinian or anybody else, to die in that war.

436
00:34:53,828 --> 00:34:57,994
[SPEAKER_06]: And as... Did you not think the Argentines should have got out of the Falklands?

437
00:34:58,134 --> 00:35:07,447
[SPEAKER_03]: I don't think they should have gone in there, but I also think there should have been an opportunity to prevent that war happening by the UN, which was being attempted at that time.

438
00:35:07,468 --> 00:35:08,369
[SPEAKER_03]: So you do think it was a Tory plot?

439
00:35:08,389 --> 00:35:09,190
[SPEAKER_03]: That was my point to you.

440
00:35:09,170 --> 00:35:10,832
[SPEAKER_03]: No, I think it was important.

441
00:35:10,892 --> 00:35:11,693
[SPEAKER_03]: Why did you say so then?

442
00:35:11,793 --> 00:35:17,579
[SPEAKER_03]: I think it was important that there should be a negotiated solution to that through the United Nations.

443
00:35:17,819 --> 00:35:18,440
[SPEAKER_03]: That surely...

444
00:35:18,460 --> 00:35:21,643
[SPEAKER_03]: If you didn't believe it was a Tory plot, why did you say you thought it was?

445
00:35:21,924 --> 00:35:28,851
[SPEAKER_03]: Jeremy, Margaret Thatcher made a great deal of the whole issue, as everybody could see at the time.

446
00:35:29,552 --> 00:35:37,320
[SPEAKER_03]: I felt that she was exploiting the situation, but there has to be, at the end of every conflict, there has to be a peace process.

447
00:35:37,300 --> 00:35:44,873
[SPEAKER_03]: Why don't we start with the objective of trying to get a peace process and use our councils through the United Nations to achieve that?

448
00:35:44,893 --> 00:36:00,861
[SPEAKER_06]: Because it's quite possible that in a couple of weeks' time, if you're sitting in Downing Street, the Chief of the Defence Staff could come to you and say, we have eyes on a man in Iraq or in Syria or in Afghanistan who is plotting a bombing campaign in Britain.

449
00:36:01,178 --> 00:36:06,575
[SPEAKER_06]: you have 20 minutes to make up your mind as to whether we take him out with a drone strike.

450
00:36:07,278 --> 00:36:11,391
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, if you think, do you think that's a Tory plot as well?

451
00:36:11,928 --> 00:36:15,475
[SPEAKER_03]: I would want to know the circumstances, the evidence and what would happen.

452
00:36:15,495 --> 00:36:16,276
[SPEAKER_06]: It's happened before.

453
00:36:16,336 --> 00:36:21,466
[SPEAKER_03]: And also what the effect it would be on innocent civilians around.

454
00:36:22,348 --> 00:36:25,193
[SPEAKER_06]: You would be prepared to take such a decision?

455
00:36:25,213 --> 00:36:27,838
[SPEAKER_06]: You would be prepared to take such a decision?

456
00:36:28,319 --> 00:36:31,585
[SPEAKER_03]: Killing somebody actually happened outside Parliament a month ago.

457
00:36:31,645 --> 00:36:32,467
[SPEAKER_03]: Yes.

458
00:36:32,487 --> 00:36:34,611
[SPEAKER_03]: And I think you have to

459
00:36:34,591 --> 00:36:36,153
[SPEAKER_03]: look at all the evidence that's there.

460
00:36:36,173 --> 00:36:39,599
[SPEAKER_03]: But you can't answer a hypothetical question without the evidence around it.

461
00:36:39,619 --> 00:36:41,121
[SPEAKER_06]: But it's not really hypothetical.

462
00:36:41,141 --> 00:36:43,825
[SPEAKER_03]: It's a completely hypothetical question.

463
00:36:44,786 --> 00:36:46,509
[SPEAKER_03]: It's a completely hypothetical question.

464
00:36:46,589 --> 00:36:49,534
[SPEAKER_03]: We have to look at the evidence that's there at the time.

465
00:36:49,554 --> 00:36:56,464
[SPEAKER_06]: We have to look at the evidence that's there at the time to make that fatal decision one way or the other.

466
00:36:57,237 --> 00:37:01,265
[SPEAKER_06]: Why then did you describe the killing of Osama bin Laden as a tragedy?

467
00:37:02,167 --> 00:37:06,074
[SPEAKER_06]: Because I think he should have been arrested and I think he should have been put on trial.

468
00:37:06,094 --> 00:37:07,076
[SPEAKER_03]: And he could have been.

469
00:37:07,096 --> 00:37:10,804
[SPEAKER_03]: You think that was a tragedy?

470
00:37:11,986 --> 00:37:18,098
[SPEAKER_03]: I think the whole Afghan experience is a tragedy and I think he should have been put on trial.

471
00:37:18,635 --> 00:37:27,334
[SPEAKER_06]: See, what bothers a lot of people is the friends that you have made in your campaign, doubtless heartfully felt for peace.

472
00:37:28,056 --> 00:37:29,459
[SPEAKER_06]: Like Hamas, for example.

473
00:37:29,860 --> 00:37:34,129
[SPEAKER_06]: You know that Hamas have killed civilians, and yet you call them your friends.

474
00:37:35,290 --> 00:37:53,887
[SPEAKER_03]: It was inclusive language at a meeting in which I was promoting the idea of a two-state solution, in which I was promoting the need for dialogue between Israel and all aspects of Palestine, including Hamas, as well as including Fatah.

475
00:37:54,047 --> 00:37:57,350
[SPEAKER_03]: I think to bring about a peace process, that is important.

476
00:37:57,370 --> 00:37:58,891
[SPEAKER_03]: Do you know what happened last night in Tel Aviv?

477
00:37:59,372 --> 00:38:04,356
[SPEAKER_03]: It was a very large demonstration of people wanting a peace process and a dialogue.

478
00:38:04,376 --> 00:38:05,297
[SPEAKER_03]: I think

479
00:38:05,277 --> 00:38:06,658
[SPEAKER_03]: Those are people you've got to work with.

480
00:38:06,878 --> 00:38:10,322
[SPEAKER_03]: You've got to work with people often you don't agree with and don't like.

481
00:38:10,342 --> 00:38:16,608
[SPEAKER_06]: You're happy to call Hamas your friends despite the fact they kill innocent women and children.

482
00:38:16,628 --> 00:38:20,631
[SPEAKER_03]: It was an inclusive piece of language in order to get a meeting underway.

483
00:38:20,812 --> 00:38:22,033
[SPEAKER_03]: I do not agree with them.

484
00:38:22,173 --> 00:38:23,254
[SPEAKER_03]: I do not support them.

485
00:38:23,854 --> 00:38:25,516
[SPEAKER_03]: I want there to be a process.

486
00:38:25,596 --> 00:38:31,061
[SPEAKER_03]: But at the end of the day, there has to be a process in which people talk to each other.

487
00:38:31,902 --> 00:38:32,382
[SPEAKER_03]: You know that.

488
00:38:33,083 --> 00:38:34,204
[SPEAKER_06]: Jeremy Corbyn, thank you.

489
00:38:35,888 --> 00:38:50,033
[SPEAKER_06]: Coming next, the Prime Minister Theresa May is here and ready to meet our audience.

490
00:38:59,041 --> 00:39:15,746
[SPEAKER_05]: This is May versus Corbyn, the battle for number 10.

491
00:39:15,987 --> 00:39:20,273
[SPEAKER_05]: It's time for our audience and you at home to meet the Prime Minister, Theresa May.

492
00:39:27,408 --> 00:39:34,083
[SPEAKER_01]: Happy birthday, by the way.

493
00:39:34,103 --> 00:39:38,453
[SPEAKER_05]: OK, well, let's get started with our first question from Martin.

494
00:39:38,553 --> 00:39:39,375
[SPEAKER_15]: Martin.

495
00:39:39,760 --> 00:39:40,701
[SPEAKER_15]: Good evening, Prime Minister.

496
00:39:41,222 --> 00:39:41,662
[SPEAKER_05]: Good evening, Martin.

497
00:39:41,682 --> 00:39:47,388
[SPEAKER_15]: As a serving police officer, I have been witness to the devastating effects of police cuts during your time as Home Secretary.

498
00:39:47,908 --> 00:39:53,554
[SPEAKER_15]: And now, after the horrendous terrorist attacks in Manchester last Monday, we have seen the need to draft in the military.

499
00:39:54,295 --> 00:39:57,078
[SPEAKER_15]: What promise can you make to increase the number of police officers?

500
00:39:57,618 --> 00:40:05,987
[SPEAKER_15]: And can I ask you to provide us with a specific number of how many extra police officers that will be recruited under your government and how you propose to fund it?

501
00:40:06,592 --> 00:40:13,322
[SPEAKER_18]: Well Martin, as a serving police officer obviously you'll be aware that we have police and counter-terrorism police.

502
00:40:13,342 --> 00:40:21,894
[SPEAKER_18]: We've been very clear that we have protected the budgets for counter-terrorism policing and we're currently protecting overall police budgets as well.

503
00:40:22,335 --> 00:40:30,828
[SPEAKER_18]: And we're ensuring that we're putting money in to enable the police to address what are actually different ways, as you will know, different types of crime.

504
00:40:30,888 --> 00:40:31,789
[SPEAKER_18]: Crime is changing.

505
00:40:32,039 --> 00:40:34,161
[SPEAKER_18]: And policing will be changing in the future.

506
00:40:34,201 --> 00:40:42,110
[SPEAKER_18]: It's why we're putting more money, for example, into cyber policing, because increasingly we see those as the sort of crimes that are having to be addressed.

507
00:40:42,830 --> 00:40:52,801
[SPEAKER_18]: We did do what was called Operation Temperer, which enabled the military to assist the police following the terrible, horrific attack that took place in Manchester.

508
00:40:52,821 --> 00:41:01,590
[SPEAKER_18]: That's been a well-prepared plan for some time, and that was put into operation and put into operation smoothly and is now being run down.

509
00:41:02,077 --> 00:41:07,918
[SPEAKER_18]: What is important is that we not only ensure we have the counter-terrorism police we need.

510
00:41:08,303 --> 00:41:12,570
[SPEAKER_18]: and the overall police that we need, but also that they have the powers that they need.

511
00:41:13,071 --> 00:41:14,854
[SPEAKER_18]: And that's what I've done as Home Secretary.

512
00:41:15,214 --> 00:41:24,329
[SPEAKER_18]: I ensured that we brought through new legislation to put powers into place, which gave the police what they were asking for in order to be able to deal with counter-terrorism.

513
00:41:24,750 --> 00:41:31,260
[SPEAKER_05]: Just to clarify for Martin, when you became Home Secretary, the staff numbers of police were 141,850.

514
00:41:31,300 --> 00:41:34,125
[SPEAKER_05]: That's September

515
00:41:34,105 --> 00:41:34,726
[SPEAKER_05]: 10.

516
00:41:35,187 --> 00:41:35,728
[SPEAKER_05]: What are they now?

517
00:41:35,748 --> 00:41:36,169
[SPEAKER_05]: 124,000.

518
00:41:36,489 --> 00:41:38,312
[SPEAKER_05]: So that's down 20,000.

519
00:41:38,432 --> 00:41:39,474
[SPEAKER_05]: That's what he's talking about.

520
00:41:39,574 --> 00:41:47,949
[SPEAKER_05]: And armed officers were nearly 7,000 in March 2010, and now... Well, we're currently having an uplift in the number of armed officers.

521
00:41:47,989 --> 00:41:53,999
[SPEAKER_18]: We agreed that not just the normal armed officers should be increased, but actually the counter-terrorism specialist officers as well.

522
00:41:54,019 --> 00:41:56,063
[SPEAKER_05]: But they were cut over six years, and you've had to put them back up.

523
00:41:56,223 --> 00:41:57,345
[SPEAKER_05]: Was that a mistake?

524
00:41:57,325 --> 00:42:09,297
[SPEAKER_18]: What we had to do when we came into government in 2010 was to ensure that we were living within our means and that was very important because of the economic situation we'd inherited.

525
00:42:09,798 --> 00:42:23,552
[SPEAKER_18]: Now what we need to do in policing terms is ensure it's not just about the numbers of police, people often focus on the numbers of police, it's actually about what the police are able to do and how they are being deployed on our streets.

526
00:42:23,612 --> 00:42:24,193
[SPEAKER_18]: As I say

527
00:42:24,477 --> 00:42:29,707
[SPEAKER_18]: In counter-terrorism policing we have protected those budgets and we're currently protecting police budgets.

528
00:42:30,088 --> 00:42:34,957
[SPEAKER_18]: But crime is changing and the sort of job that the police officers need to do is changing.

529
00:42:35,298 --> 00:42:40,949
[SPEAKER_18]: That's why we're also putting extra money into things like cybercrime because that's today's world.

530
00:42:41,329 --> 00:42:46,840
[SPEAKER_18]: So a government has to ensure that we're keeping abreast with the changes that take place

531
00:42:46,820 --> 00:42:50,146
[SPEAKER_18]: with the challenges that there are out there that we need to deal with.

532
00:42:50,627 --> 00:42:52,751
[SPEAKER_18]: And of course the terrorist threat is severe.

533
00:42:52,811 --> 00:42:54,875
[SPEAKER_18]: That's where it is at the moment.

534
00:42:55,315 --> 00:43:02,168
[SPEAKER_18]: But that's why we ensure that our police, our security service, have that counter-terrorism budget.

535
00:43:02,228 --> 00:43:04,813
[SPEAKER_18]: We are increasing the budgets for our security services as well.

536
00:43:05,274 --> 00:43:08,539
[SPEAKER_18]: But also that they have the powers they need to do the job.

537
00:43:08,560 --> 00:43:09,942
[SPEAKER_18]: Just a quick come back, Martin.

538
00:43:11,440 --> 00:43:18,675
[SPEAKER_15]: I appreciate you're protecting the budgets but we still need the staff to carry out the role of a police officer of keeping the public safe.

539
00:43:20,279 --> 00:43:23,205
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay well let's move on to Philip.

540
00:43:23,455 --> 00:43:32,426
[SPEAKER_19]: Prime Minister, in my first job 74 years ago, I owned the princely sum of 31 shillings a week, which is £1.55 in current money.

541
00:43:33,207 --> 00:43:40,595
[SPEAKER_19]: I lived in a council house with my four siblings and my parents in the George Orwell's Wigan of the 1930s.

542
00:43:42,177 --> 00:43:48,805
[SPEAKER_19]: Over the years, due to our hard work and the work of my late wife, we came to own our own home, and it is now mortgage-free.

543
00:43:50,540 --> 00:44:04,502
[SPEAKER_19]: I don't like the prospect of being unable to leave it to our family with a greatly eroded value, which I fear is what would happen if you were to introduce your so-called dementia tax.

544
00:44:04,522 --> 00:44:10,692
[SPEAKER_19]: So why, Prime Minister, should we, in my generation, vote for you?

545
00:44:17,759 --> 00:44:23,227
[SPEAKER_18]: Philip, thank you, because you've raised an issue which I know a lot of people are looking at and thinking about.

546
00:44:23,668 --> 00:44:33,562
[SPEAKER_18]: And it's a really important issue because one of the great challenges that we face as a society, and that government faces, is the fact that our society is ageing.

547
00:44:33,582 --> 00:44:43,536
[SPEAKER_18]: We see more people, it's great that people are living longer, but of course that has an impact in terms of the services we have to provide and ensuring people can have the dignity in their old age.

548
00:44:43,616 --> 00:44:46,821
[SPEAKER_18]: Now the situation, as I'm sure you know at the moment is,

549
00:44:46,801 --> 00:44:52,675
[SPEAKER_18]: that if you require care and you have savings of more than £23,000, you have to pay for that care.

550
00:44:52,735 --> 00:44:59,310
[SPEAKER_18]: And if the care you require is residential care, then the value of your house is taken into account.

551
00:44:59,771 --> 00:45:02,397
[SPEAKER_18]: So what happens is people are paying for care

552
00:45:02,377 --> 00:45:14,381
[SPEAKER_18]: People are finding that they are having to sell their house, many people are having to sell their house to pay those care bills and many find that they're not able to leave the money to their families.

553
00:45:14,862 --> 00:45:20,453
[SPEAKER_18]: Now I want to take those risks away and that's what the proposals I've put forward are about.

554
00:45:20,433 --> 00:45:25,623
[SPEAKER_18]: It's about ensuring that nobody is going to have to sell their house to pay for care in their lifetime.

555
00:45:26,304 --> 00:45:32,516
[SPEAKER_18]: It's about ensuring that £100,000 of savings of assets are protected to pass on to the family.

556
00:45:33,298 --> 00:45:39,690
[SPEAKER_18]: We'll put an absolute cap on the level of money that people have to spend on care.

557
00:45:39,670 --> 00:45:45,499
[SPEAKER_18]: And I think what we're doing is ensuring that we can have a sustainable solution for the long term.

558
00:45:45,759 --> 00:45:52,129
[SPEAKER_18]: If I can just give one figure Faisal, in 10 years time there will be 2 million more people aged over 75.

559
00:45:52,390 --> 00:45:57,538
[SPEAKER_18]: If we don't address the issue of our social care system now then it is going to collapse.

560
00:45:57,999 --> 00:46:04,108
[SPEAKER_18]: We need to do it and do it in a way that's fairer to younger generations and that's what my plans are for.

561
00:46:04,088 --> 00:46:10,300
[SPEAKER_05]: Can you just clarify for Philip and people at home, what is the cap?

562
00:46:10,721 --> 00:46:12,845
[SPEAKER_05]: Is it a manifesto policy that there will be a cap?

563
00:46:13,325 --> 00:46:14,548
[SPEAKER_18]: There will be a cap, yes.

564
00:46:14,608 --> 00:46:18,054
[SPEAKER_18]: What we set out in the manifesto is the principles of our position.

565
00:46:18,636 --> 00:46:20,679
[SPEAKER_18]: I then saw a lot of scaremongering about that.

566
00:46:20,740 --> 00:46:22,603
[SPEAKER_18]: I heard a lot of scaremongering about it.

567
00:46:22,583 --> 00:46:25,466
[SPEAKER_18]: and recognise that people would be worried as a result of that.

568
00:46:25,486 --> 00:46:26,027
[SPEAKER_18]: 100,000?

569
00:46:26,047 --> 00:46:26,567
[SPEAKER_18]: 500,000?

570
00:46:26,607 --> 00:46:28,129
[SPEAKER_18]: We clarified that there will be a cap.

571
00:46:28,509 --> 00:46:31,292
[SPEAKER_18]: But what we will do, Faisal, is not just put a figure on it.

572
00:46:31,693 --> 00:46:36,037
[SPEAKER_18]: What we will do is publish a green paper, a consultation document.

573
00:46:36,478 --> 00:46:37,358
[SPEAKER_18]: We'll listen to people.

574
00:46:37,378 --> 00:46:38,360
[SPEAKER_18]: We'll listen to voters.

575
00:46:38,420 --> 00:46:42,143
[SPEAKER_18]: We'll listen to charities and organisations working with older people.

576
00:46:42,544 --> 00:46:45,727
[SPEAKER_18]: We'll take people's views on where that cap should be.

577
00:46:46,048 --> 00:46:47,549
[SPEAKER_18]: And I think that's the fairer way to do it.

578
00:46:48,090 --> 00:46:48,510
[SPEAKER_18]: OK. Amanda.

579
00:46:49,471 --> 00:46:50,312
[SPEAKER_17]: Good evening.

580
00:46:50,917 --> 00:46:57,344
[SPEAKER_17]: Are we dividing England and Scotland by allowing a winter fuel allowance for over-60s in Scotland?

581
00:46:58,645 --> 00:46:59,406
[SPEAKER_17]: Is this fair?

582
00:47:00,567 --> 00:47:20,468
[SPEAKER_18]: Well we have a situation as you know where there's a devolved government in Scotland and they have the ability to make separate decisions on a whole variety of issues affecting people in Scotland and they've been given extra powers in relation to dealing with welfare so it is up to them to make that decision as to how

583
00:47:20,448 --> 00:47:24,453
[SPEAKER_18]: they choose to apply certain welfare benefits.

584
00:47:25,233 --> 00:47:46,978
[SPEAKER_18]: We will, we have said and we will in government means test the winter fuel payment and the reason for doing that is this, at the moment we have a situation where pensions who are better off are getting that help and support where you see working families who might be struggling not getting that sort of support and I think it's right and I think you know I've met

585
00:47:46,958 --> 00:47:51,007
[SPEAKER_18]: pensioners who've said to me that they don't think they should get that winter fuel payment.

586
00:47:51,468 --> 00:47:55,175
[SPEAKER_18]: What we will do with the money that's released is we'll put it into health and social care.

587
00:47:55,556 --> 00:48:03,533
[SPEAKER_18]: So it will be going towards actually ensuring that those systems are providing better quality care for older people and others.

588
00:48:03,884 --> 00:48:07,408
[SPEAKER_05]: So Prime Minister, we know that Scottish pensioners will keep the winter fuel allowance.

589
00:48:07,468 --> 00:48:10,851
[SPEAKER_05]: Can you tell us how many English pensioners will lose it?

590
00:48:11,372 --> 00:48:15,416
[SPEAKER_05]: The IFS have assumed six million, the Resolution Foundation ten million.

591
00:48:15,737 --> 00:48:17,919
[SPEAKER_05]: It's clearly several million isn't it?

592
00:48:18,379 --> 00:48:33,115
[SPEAKER_18]: Well what we're going to do Faisal, I'm sorry it's exactly the same as I've just said on the social care cap, is once again I think this is an issue where we need not just to pull out a figure in an election campaign, but actually to listen to people, to talk to people,

593
00:48:33,297 --> 00:48:38,182
[SPEAKER_18]: to take people's views and then make a proposal as government.

594
00:48:38,202 --> 00:48:39,683
[SPEAKER_18]: So there's a proper consultation.

595
00:48:40,103 --> 00:48:54,077
[SPEAKER_18]: So we're actually hearing from voters, we're hearing from organisations and charities and others who work with older people about what they think is the right level to set that threshold for winter fuel payments at.

596
00:48:54,377 --> 00:48:59,622
[SPEAKER_18]: But the key thing, the key principle that would drive what we do is that less well-off pensioners will be protected.

597
00:49:00,863 --> 00:49:02,865
[SPEAKER_05]: OK, all right, let's move on to Nicola.

598
00:49:03,233 --> 00:49:03,674
[SPEAKER_09]: Good evening.

599
00:49:04,715 --> 00:49:13,807
[SPEAKER_09]: As a teacher and mother of two, I am incredibly concerned by your proposed changes to school funding, with my local constituency of Batley and Spen one of the worst affected areas.

600
00:49:14,528 --> 00:49:18,734
[SPEAKER_09]: Prime Minister, despite your manifesto promises, these cuts are clearly unsustainable.

601
00:49:19,254 --> 00:49:24,381
[SPEAKER_09]: Are you prepared to change your current plans to prevent further damage to our schools?

602
00:49:30,841 --> 00:49:36,472
[SPEAKER_18]: Nicola, what we will do in government is put further record levels of funding into schools.

603
00:49:37,354 --> 00:49:42,164
[SPEAKER_18]: But we also do want to look at ensuring that the money is being distributed in a fair way.

604
00:49:42,945 --> 00:49:48,917
[SPEAKER_18]: And as you probably know, there are some schools in the country today that may receive twice the amount of funding

605
00:49:49,117 --> 00:49:52,362
[SPEAKER_18]: for a pupil that other schools receive.

606
00:49:52,823 --> 00:49:57,331
[SPEAKER_18]: I think it's important that we see a fair way of funding our schools.

607
00:49:57,952 --> 00:50:05,725
[SPEAKER_18]: What we're committed to is ensuring that as we introduce that, schools won't see any cash reduction in their level of funding.

608
00:50:05,705 --> 00:50:11,415
[SPEAKER_18]: But I actually want to do more than that because I believe that education is absolutely crucial.

609
00:50:11,435 --> 00:50:14,901
[SPEAKER_18]: We want our youngsters to get the best possible start in life.

610
00:50:15,482 --> 00:50:20,872
[SPEAKER_18]: And that's why I want to see a more diverse system of schools available for people.

611
00:50:21,173 --> 00:50:25,300
[SPEAKER_18]: I want to bring in some of the expertise that we see in universities.

612
00:50:25,465 --> 00:50:28,890
[SPEAKER_18]: For example, in supporting schools, there are some good examples of that at the moment.

613
00:50:29,210 --> 00:50:30,132
[SPEAKER_18]: Let's do more of that.

614
00:50:30,532 --> 00:50:36,160
[SPEAKER_18]: Let's make sure that every child has a good school place, and a school place that is right for them.

615
00:50:36,521 --> 00:50:42,229
[SPEAKER_18]: Because that's about ensuring they get the best possible start in life, to be the best that they can.

616
00:50:42,369 --> 00:50:49,920
[SPEAKER_18]: Because I want our society to be one where it's down to your talents and hard work how far you go, and not where you came from or who your parents are.

617
00:50:50,407 --> 00:50:53,232
[SPEAKER_05]: I think Nicola's question was about per-pupil funding in real terms.

618
00:50:53,252 --> 00:50:56,236
[SPEAKER_05]: You've said it's going to go up £4 billion, but that is going down.

619
00:50:56,317 --> 00:50:58,320
[SPEAKER_05]: In real terms, per-pupil, it is going down.

620
00:50:58,340 --> 00:50:59,221
[SPEAKER_05]: Can you clarify that?

621
00:50:59,482 --> 00:51:03,689
[SPEAKER_18]: Nobody can guarantee the real-terms per-pupil funding increase.

622
00:51:04,169 --> 00:51:07,034
[SPEAKER_18]: In the Labour Party's manifesto we know the figures don't add up.

623
00:51:07,455 --> 00:51:09,478
[SPEAKER_18]: What is important is that as we look

624
00:51:09,762 --> 00:51:21,770
[SPEAKER_18]: What we need to do is to ensure we will put those record levels of funding into schools.

625
00:51:22,231 --> 00:51:28,024
[SPEAKER_18]: We need to ensure that we get that better spread of funding in terms of the fair funding formula.

626
00:51:28,004 --> 00:51:44,943
[SPEAKER_18]: But I also say this, if you look at what happens in education, it's not just people are focusing on funding, but actually we need to ensure that we do see good or outstanding schools and more good or outstanding places in good or outstanding schools for children.

627
00:51:45,003 --> 00:51:48,567
[SPEAKER_18]: We've seen the number increase over the last seven years.

628
00:51:48,967 --> 00:51:52,931
[SPEAKER_18]: We need to carry on doing that so that there is a good school place for every child.

629
00:51:53,452 --> 00:51:57,977
[SPEAKER_18]: And that isn't just about funding, it's about a whole variety of things that go to make up

630
00:51:58,126 --> 00:52:00,346
[SPEAKER_18]: really good education for children.

631
00:52:01,112 --> 00:52:02,787
[SPEAKER_05]: Okay, next question, Joy.

632
00:52:03,053 --> 00:52:21,052
[SPEAKER_11]: Theresa May, could you please justify to me why I have leaflets saved at home delivered to me by my local Conservatives before the EU referendum stating clearly that we will save £350 million per week for the NHS if we leave the EU.

633
00:52:21,092 --> 00:52:28,200
[SPEAKER_11]: That lie is the only reason why I, and I'm sure many others here tonight possibly, decided to vote leave.

634
00:52:32,686 --> 00:52:43,201
[SPEAKER_18]: There were a number of claims made during the referendum campaign on both sides of the argument and there were some passionately held views and some really passionate arguments on both sides.

635
00:52:43,802 --> 00:52:49,190
[SPEAKER_18]: I think what's important now is that we ensure that we get the best possible deal from Brexit.

636
00:52:49,650 --> 00:52:52,554
[SPEAKER_18]: That is about negotiating a really good deal for Britain.

637
00:52:53,075 --> 00:53:01,427
[SPEAKER_18]: It is about ensuring that in future we won't be sending vast sums of money to the European Union every year as we do as members of the EU.

638
00:53:01,407 --> 00:53:07,472
[SPEAKER_18]: And we will be able to look at what, as funding comes back, how we use that funding.

639
00:53:07,853 --> 00:53:14,158
[SPEAKER_18]: But it is important that we get that best possible deal because it underpins so much else of what we want to do.

640
00:53:14,779 --> 00:53:19,603
[SPEAKER_18]: And we can only get that deal if we've got a plan to go in there and really stand up for Britain.

641
00:53:20,544 --> 00:53:23,987
[SPEAKER_18]: And the negotiations will start 11 days after Election Day.

642
00:53:24,467 --> 00:53:31,313
[SPEAKER_18]: So we have to know what we're doing, we have to have a strong hand in the negotiations, and be very clear about getting the best possible deal for Britain.

643
00:53:31,782 --> 00:53:47,928
[SPEAKER_10]: Prime Minister, I'm a midwife in Devon and I believe the wealth of a nation lies in the health of its workforce.

644
00:53:47,948 --> 00:53:56,001
[SPEAKER_10]: How do you justify the chronic underfunding of the NHS that I see at work, considering that we now have one of the lowest budgets according to GDP?

645
00:54:02,866 --> 00:54:11,542
[SPEAKER_18]: Once again, if we look at the health service, and obviously you work in the health service, so you know the enormity of the task that the health service faces.

646
00:54:11,602 --> 00:54:14,508
[SPEAKER_18]: We're making greater demands on the health service every year.

647
00:54:14,568 --> 00:54:22,883
[SPEAKER_18]: The overall figure is we're spending over the five years up to 2020, we'll be spending half a trillion pounds in total.

648
00:54:22,863 --> 00:54:24,426
[SPEAKER_18]: on the National Health Service.

649
00:54:25,469 --> 00:54:29,117
[SPEAKER_18]: And we do need to make sure that money is being spent well, of course.

650
00:54:29,638 --> 00:54:35,250
[SPEAKER_18]: So we are increasing the funding into the health service and will increase funding into the health service in the future.

651
00:54:35,571 --> 00:54:41,023
[SPEAKER_18]: And we're committed to that in our manifesto, both in terms of buildings and technology, but also in terms

652
00:54:41,240 --> 00:54:47,308
[SPEAKER_18]: of increasing the per head funding for the National Health Service in real terms every year.

653
00:54:48,209 --> 00:54:48,930
[SPEAKER_18]: It's important.

654
00:54:49,050 --> 00:54:50,772
[SPEAKER_18]: We all rely on the health service.

655
00:54:51,273 --> 00:55:01,245
[SPEAKER_18]: We all know people either who work in the health service like yourself, who've been through the health service, who've had great care and attention from the fantastic staff in the health service.

656
00:55:01,766 --> 00:55:09,576
[SPEAKER_18]: That's why we're ensuring that we are putting more money into the NHS and more money for the future as well as what is happening at the moment.

657
00:55:09,826 --> 00:55:16,914
[SPEAKER_18]: We want that first class NHS, but we can only do that if we have a really strong economy to pay for it.

658
00:55:17,595 --> 00:55:32,292
[SPEAKER_18]: And that's where the Brexit negotiations, but so much else actually comes in, because it's making sure we get that right deal for Britain from Brexit, that we can build on the strong economy and the economic progress we've made in the last few years.

659
00:55:32,753 --> 00:55:37,238
[SPEAKER_18]: Because if we do that, then we have that money to fund that first class National Health Service.

660
00:55:37,539 --> 00:55:38,820
[SPEAKER_18]: That's what we're committed to.

661
00:55:41,770 --> 00:55:44,714
[SPEAKER_05]: OK, what did you think of that answer?

662
00:55:44,734 --> 00:55:45,315
[SPEAKER_05]: Freya, back to you.

663
00:55:46,717 --> 00:55:49,742
[SPEAKER_10]: I see a lot of efficiency savings that are actually cuts.

664
00:55:50,283 --> 00:55:51,605
[SPEAKER_10]: I see hospitals closing.

665
00:55:52,726 --> 00:55:57,093
[SPEAKER_10]: I see staff that are at their wits' end because they can't give the care that they want to give.

666
00:55:58,235 --> 00:55:59,196
[SPEAKER_10]: I'll believe it when I see it.

667
00:56:04,223 --> 00:56:05,445
[SPEAKER_05]: OK, let's go to Sandeep.

668
00:56:05,465 --> 00:56:06,727
[SPEAKER_05]: Sandeep.

669
00:56:06,747 --> 00:56:07,288
[SPEAKER_05]: Where's Sandeep?

670
00:56:08,956 --> 00:56:11,499
[SPEAKER_05]: Hello Prime Minister.

671
00:56:12,440 --> 00:56:12,620
[SPEAKER_04]: Hello.

672
00:56:12,921 --> 00:56:32,584
[SPEAKER_04]: Prime Minister, describing yourself and being described as a bloody difficult woman may be helpful in Brexit negotiations with the EU, but do you think the same attitude when applied to domestic policy, such as welfare reform and cuts, have reinforced the image of the Conservatives being called the nasty party again?

673
00:56:36,952 --> 00:56:56,819
[SPEAKER_18]: When I was described in the terms that you've said as a difficult woman, I think it was about because my colleague who used that term saw me as somebody who actually stood by what I thought was right and was willing to fight for what I believe is the right thing to do.

674
00:56:57,440 --> 00:56:58,442
[SPEAKER_18]: And that's what drives me.

675
00:56:58,602 --> 00:57:01,265
[SPEAKER_18]: It's doing what is the right thing by the country.

676
00:57:02,067 --> 00:57:06,773
[SPEAKER_18]: And sometimes you have to be difficult in order to do that.

677
00:57:06,753 --> 00:57:13,364
[SPEAKER_18]: If I look at what's coming ahead to this country, we stand at a very important moment in our history.

678
00:57:13,985 --> 00:57:19,474
[SPEAKER_18]: We have the opportunity now to really change this country for the better for the future.

679
00:57:20,175 --> 00:57:30,111
[SPEAKER_18]: And that is about tough negotiations for Brexit, but it's also about facing up to those domestic challenges, domestic challenges like the ageing society, like the changing

680
00:57:30,091 --> 00:57:33,976
[SPEAKER_18]: face we see in the workplace, the increased technology in the workplace.

681
00:57:34,616 --> 00:57:42,546
[SPEAKER_18]: All of these are things that we need to have a government that recognises it, is open about those issues and is willing to find ways of addressing them.

682
00:57:43,207 --> 00:57:53,179
[SPEAKER_18]: And if in order to address them and do the right thing by the country, it takes being a difficult woman, then that's exactly what I will be.

683
00:57:53,918 --> 00:57:57,902
[SPEAKER_05]: Prime Minister, the question was about Nazi party applied to domestic policy.

684
00:57:58,322 --> 00:58:01,505
[SPEAKER_05]: And you're asking fairly uniquely for a massive majority.

685
00:58:01,525 --> 00:58:03,727
[SPEAKER_05]: You're already Prime Minister, you want a really big majority.

686
00:58:03,987 --> 00:58:05,849
[SPEAKER_05]: That will also apply to domestic policy.

687
00:58:06,430 --> 00:58:12,636
[SPEAKER_05]: And you voted for things that subsequently you turned on, like tax credits cuts in 2015.

688
00:58:13,556 --> 00:58:20,483
[SPEAKER_05]: Isn't that what will not be able to be turned around when you have a larger majority, if that's what you get?

689
00:58:20,716 --> 00:58:33,935
[SPEAKER_18]: Well, you say, what I'm doing, Faisal, is actually going out across the country asking people, yes, for me to gain their trust so that they will support me at this election.

690
00:58:34,395 --> 00:58:41,225
[SPEAKER_18]: Because I think it is important to have a strong hand in the negotiations for Brexit, to have that strong mandate for those negotiations.

691
00:58:42,147 --> 00:58:46,433
[SPEAKER_18]: But we also have a lot of challenges to face here in this country.

692
00:58:47,013 --> 00:58:48,816
[SPEAKER_18]: And as I've said, there are

693
00:58:48,796 --> 00:59:07,828
[SPEAKER_18]: Brexit is one of the challenges, getting that right, our ageing society is another, the divisions within our society is another and the issue of making sure we have a strong economy and facing the impact of changing technology and the impact that's having on our lives and our workplaces, everybody will know.

694
00:59:07,888 --> 00:59:12,255
[SPEAKER_18]: These are big challenges ahead and the domestic policies that I've set out

695
00:59:12,235 --> 00:59:29,805
[SPEAKER_18]: our policies to address those challenges and some of them will involve difficult choices but I think it's right if I'm saying to people I want a mandate to be Prime Minister and to have the government of this country that we're actually open with people that there will be some hard choices.

696
00:59:30,427 --> 00:59:36,042
[SPEAKER_05]: OK, well, that brings us to the end of our second question and answer session of the evening.

697
00:59:36,403 --> 00:59:37,846
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you very much, Prime Minister.

698
00:59:37,866 --> 00:59:38,127
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

699
00:59:38,147 --> 00:59:38,508
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you.

700
00:59:38,528 --> 00:59:39,711
[SPEAKER_05]: Thanks again to the audience for their questions.

701
00:59:40,273 --> 00:59:44,183
[SPEAKER_05]: Coming next, Theresa May sits down with Jeremy Paxman.

702
00:59:58,574 --> 01:00:22,219
[SPEAKER_06]: Theresa May, when did you realise that you'd got the wrong answer to the biggest question of our times in politics?

703
01:00:24,376 --> 01:00:26,880
[SPEAKER_18]: Well, I'm tempted to ask you, Jeremy, what you think.

704
01:00:27,000 --> 01:00:28,542
[SPEAKER_18]: Do you mean that you're talking about Brexit?

705
01:00:28,983 --> 01:00:29,564
[SPEAKER_18]: Well, of course.

706
01:00:29,904 --> 01:00:30,125
[SPEAKER_18]: Right.

707
01:00:30,986 --> 01:00:34,431
[SPEAKER_18]: Well, there are lots of challenges in our politics at the moment.

708
01:00:34,731 --> 01:00:36,614
[SPEAKER_18]: There are lots of challenges that the government face.

709
01:00:37,135 --> 01:00:42,503
[SPEAKER_06]: I'm just curious, what was it convinced you that Brexit was so bad for Britain?

710
01:00:43,495 --> 01:00:50,735
[SPEAKER_18]: I set out my reasons for deciding that we should, on balance, stay within the European Union.

711
01:00:51,136 --> 01:00:52,039
[SPEAKER_18]: I voted to remain.

712
01:00:52,119 --> 01:00:53,162
[SPEAKER_18]: I campaigned to remain.

713
01:00:53,463 --> 01:00:55,007
[SPEAKER_18]: When did you change your mind?

714
01:00:55,274 --> 01:01:03,108
[SPEAKER_18]: The British people were given the choice and the British people decided that they wanted the United Kingdom to leave the European Union.

715
01:01:03,128 --> 01:01:07,435
[SPEAKER_06]: So you're now stuck with trying to deliver something you believe is bad for this country.

716
01:01:07,756 --> 01:01:12,103
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm delivering what I believe the British people want their government to deliver.

717
01:01:12,584 --> 01:01:13,906
[SPEAKER_18]: And I think it's very important.

718
01:01:13,966 --> 01:01:17,012
[SPEAKER_18]: I think it's not just an issue about Brexit itself.

719
01:01:17,432 --> 01:01:20,758
[SPEAKER_18]: It's actually an issue to me about trust in politicians.

720
01:01:20,738 --> 01:01:21,700
[SPEAKER_06]: Hang on a second.

721
01:01:22,060 --> 01:01:32,977
[SPEAKER_06]: You said in March last year that we would be more secure, more prosperous and more influential, virtually in those words, if we stayed in the European Union.

722
01:01:33,198 --> 01:01:34,640
[SPEAKER_06]: And now you want to take us out of it.

723
01:01:34,981 --> 01:01:39,608
[SPEAKER_18]: And I also said that the sky wouldn't fall in if we left the European Union.

724
01:01:39,588 --> 01:01:41,672
[SPEAKER_18]: So you have changed your mind, have you?

725
01:01:41,692 --> 01:01:42,794
[SPEAKER_18]: We gave people the choice.

726
01:01:43,014 --> 01:01:43,756
[SPEAKER_06]: You've changed your mind?

727
01:01:43,936 --> 01:01:45,479
[SPEAKER_18]: I'll answer that in a minute.

728
01:01:45,499 --> 01:01:50,688
[SPEAKER_18]: We gave people the choice, Jeremy, and the British people decided to leave the European Union.

729
01:01:51,169 --> 01:01:57,981
[SPEAKER_18]: And I think it's important for them to see their politicians delivering on that choice and respecting the will of the people.

730
01:01:58,442 --> 01:02:01,869
[SPEAKER_06]: And what I think...

731
01:02:01,889 --> 01:02:02,710
[SPEAKER_06]: APPLAUSE OK, so you've changed your mind.

732
01:02:03,871 --> 01:02:06,515
[SPEAKER_18]: What I am now doing is... Have you changed your mind?

733
01:02:06,535 --> 01:02:09,159
[SPEAKER_18]: I think there are huge opportunities... Have you changed your mind?

734
01:02:09,460 --> 01:02:13,666
[SPEAKER_18]: Jeremy, I know that you have used this tactic and you want...

735
01:02:13,786 --> 01:02:15,208
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm just trying to get an answer.

736
01:02:15,249 --> 01:02:16,991
[SPEAKER_06]: That's all you can say, yes or no.

737
01:02:17,011 --> 01:02:18,413
[SPEAKER_06]: I haven't changed my mind.

738
01:02:18,514 --> 01:02:19,976
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, I have changed my mind.

739
01:02:20,196 --> 01:02:22,740
[SPEAKER_18]: I take the view...

740
01:02:22,720 --> 01:02:24,742
[SPEAKER_18]: that we can make a success of Brexit.

741
01:02:25,323 --> 01:02:28,226
[SPEAKER_18]: I take the view that the British people want us to make that success.

742
01:02:28,246 --> 01:02:29,187
[SPEAKER_18]: But you don't believe in it?

743
01:02:29,207 --> 01:02:29,567
[SPEAKER_18]: Of course.

744
01:02:29,968 --> 01:02:41,180
[SPEAKER_18]: Jeremy, as Prime Minister, I've been out there already ensuring that the negotiations are going to start and I want to ensure that there's a strong hand in those negotiations.

745
01:02:41,380 --> 01:02:45,184
[SPEAKER_18]: I believe in making a success of Brexit for the whole of the United Kingdom.

746
01:02:45,204 --> 01:02:46,866
[SPEAKER_06]: But you don't really believe in it, do you?

747
01:02:47,187 --> 01:02:49,369
[SPEAKER_18]: I believe in making a success of Brexit.

748
01:02:49,923 --> 01:02:51,067
[SPEAKER_06]: Let me look at it another way.

749
01:02:51,227 --> 01:03:02,042
[SPEAKER_06]: How was it that people like Boris Johnson, Michael Gove, David Davis, Priti Patel, even Andrea Leadsom, they all got it right and you got it wrong?

750
01:03:03,119 --> 01:03:08,248
[SPEAKER_18]: I voted... Well, there's no gain saying the fact that I campaigned to remain and voted to remain.

751
01:03:08,408 --> 01:03:10,572
[SPEAKER_18]: Sure, but you still think it's a duff idea.

752
01:03:10,792 --> 01:03:14,639
[SPEAKER_06]: I said it was a balanced... You still think it's a duff idea, don't you?

753
01:03:14,659 --> 01:03:17,203
[SPEAKER_18]: No, I think that... You haven't changed your mind.

754
01:03:17,223 --> 01:03:20,669
[SPEAKER_18]: Look, the referendum drew a line under those debates.

755
01:03:20,990 --> 01:03:24,175
[SPEAKER_18]: What the referendum did was took the view of the British people.

756
01:03:24,556 --> 01:03:28,603
[SPEAKER_18]: Now, I think it's right that we do that now, and I think, I genuinely think,

757
01:03:28,583 --> 01:03:37,935
[SPEAKER_18]: that if we get Brexit right, and this is really important for us, if we get Brexit right, we can make a real success of the opportunities that open up for us.

758
01:03:38,275 --> 01:03:41,499
[SPEAKER_18]: But we can only do that if we grasp those opportunities.

759
01:03:41,559 --> 01:03:42,821
[SPEAKER_18]: But you still think it's a bad idea.

760
01:03:42,841 --> 01:03:46,766
[SPEAKER_18]: No, I believe we're doing the right thing in making a success of Brexit.

761
01:03:47,927 --> 01:03:51,852
[SPEAKER_06]: Well, of course you want to make a success of it.

762
01:03:51,872 --> 01:03:55,857
[SPEAKER_06]: Can we look at something else that you've changed your mind on, or perhaps not changed your mind on?

763
01:03:56,098 --> 01:03:57,139
[SPEAKER_06]: Social care.

764
01:03:58,199 --> 01:04:04,576
[SPEAKER_06]: Now, you had a manifesto commitment which said there would be a cap on the cost of social care.

765
01:04:04,596 --> 01:04:06,962
[SPEAKER_06]: Then your latest manifesto dropped that.

766
01:04:06,982 --> 01:04:10,631
[SPEAKER_06]: And for clarification, the health secretary said there will be no cap.

767
01:04:11,033 --> 01:04:14,301
[SPEAKER_06]: And four days later, you said there will be a cap.

768
01:04:15,243 --> 01:04:22,190
[SPEAKER_18]: What Jeremy Hunt was talking about and what we referred to in our manifesto was a specific proposal.

769
01:04:22,230 --> 01:04:29,498
[SPEAKER_18]: This proposal was put forward by Andrew Dilnot a few years ago when he was asked by government to look at the social care issue.

770
01:04:30,038 --> 01:04:36,665
[SPEAKER_18]: And if I just explain why we rejected that Dilnot proposal, Jeremy, it was because for two reasons.

771
01:04:36,825 --> 01:04:41,250
[SPEAKER_18]: First of all, because it was going to be paid for out of general taxation.

772
01:04:41,230 --> 01:04:50,418
[SPEAKER_18]: And secondly, because that Deal Not proposal protected wealthier pensioners, but did nothing to protect pensioners on modest incomes.

773
01:04:50,919 --> 01:04:54,242
[SPEAKER_18]: Now the proposals I've put forward actually do that.

774
01:04:54,402 --> 01:04:57,024
[SPEAKER_18]: They do help pensioners on modest incomes.

775
01:04:57,605 --> 01:05:04,711
[SPEAKER_18]: And crucially, they ensure we have a long-term sustainable solution for social care.

776
01:05:04,731 --> 01:05:11,237
[SPEAKER_06]: Okay, you have said earlier that it's very important that people can trust their politicians and their governments.

777
01:05:11,217 --> 01:05:18,190
[SPEAKER_06]: Can I ask you, explicitly, unambiguously, what will the cap be?

778
01:05:19,182 --> 01:05:24,188
[SPEAKER_18]: Well, as I've just answered, I'm not going to give you a different answer from the one I've given Faisal.

779
01:05:25,230 --> 01:05:27,212
[SPEAKER_18]: It's not about not knowing, Jeremy.

780
01:05:27,633 --> 01:05:30,777
[SPEAKER_18]: It's about thinking what... Well, you don't know, do you?

781
01:05:30,997 --> 01:05:34,101
[SPEAKER_18]: It's about thinking what the right approach is to get to that figure.

782
01:05:34,542 --> 01:05:35,223
[SPEAKER_06]: But you don't know.

783
01:05:35,523 --> 01:05:43,333
[SPEAKER_18]: What we want to do is to ask, is to consult, is to listen, and then to determine what that cut will be.

784
01:05:43,313 --> 01:05:46,157
[SPEAKER_06]: Have you even thought what the cost to the taxpayer will be?

785
01:05:46,177 --> 01:05:56,670
[SPEAKER_18]: I think that's only fair to people, that we actually go through that consultation and say to people and take people's views as we determine that cap.

786
01:05:56,690 --> 01:06:01,856
[SPEAKER_06]: Just at a philosophical level, you said you went into politics to help the just about managing.

787
01:06:02,557 --> 01:06:11,008
[SPEAKER_06]: How is enabling rich people to pass on wealth to the next generation helping the just about managing?

788
01:06:17,350 --> 01:06:22,236
[SPEAKER_18]: What is helping is ensuring that we don't have a long-term solution.

789
01:06:22,276 --> 01:06:22,796
[SPEAKER_06]: That wasn't my question.

790
01:06:22,816 --> 01:06:23,037
[SPEAKER_18]: No, no.

791
01:06:23,417 --> 01:06:25,680
[SPEAKER_06]: No, my question was how it helped the just about managing.

792
01:06:25,700 --> 01:06:27,262
[SPEAKER_18]: And I'm answering your question, Jeremy.

793
01:06:27,282 --> 01:06:27,982
[SPEAKER_18]: You're not.

794
01:06:28,002 --> 01:06:31,547
[SPEAKER_18]: You have asked me about the just about managing and how they're being helped.

795
01:06:32,027 --> 01:06:39,696
[SPEAKER_18]: And what I'm going to point out is that if you have a social care system which relies on taxing those just about managing

796
01:06:39,676 --> 01:06:43,160
[SPEAKER_18]: at higher levels, that's not helping them.

797
01:06:43,681 --> 01:06:58,118
[SPEAKER_18]: What we're doing is putting forward a proposal which means that people don't have to sell their house in their lifetime to pay for care, it means they can pass on savings to their children, and it means there will be that cap.

798
01:06:58,138 --> 01:07:01,001
[SPEAKER_18]: But it's fair across the generations.

799
01:07:01,021 --> 01:07:06,628
[SPEAKER_18]: And there are older people today who worry that their children and grandchildren won't have a better future.

800
01:07:07,807 --> 01:07:10,314
[SPEAKER_06]: Can we look at something else on which you've changed your mind?

801
01:07:11,438 --> 01:07:19,260
[SPEAKER_06]: Only this March, in the Budget, you proposed to increase national insurance contributions from the self-employed.

802
01:07:20,464 --> 01:07:23,031
[SPEAKER_06]: Within a week, you backed down from that.

803
01:07:25,593 --> 01:07:26,274
[SPEAKER_06]: You accept that?

804
01:07:26,294 --> 01:07:27,416
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes, I accept that.

805
01:07:27,436 --> 01:07:43,703
[SPEAKER_06]: And we very clearly stated at the time... You see, what one's bound to say is, if I was sitting in Brussels and I was looking at you as the person I had to negotiate with, I'd think, she's a blowhard who collapses at the first sign of gunfire.

806
01:07:50,078 --> 01:08:05,718
[SPEAKER_18]: I think, Jeremy, you'll find that what the people in Brussels look at is the record that I had of negotiating with them in Brussels and delivering for this country on a number of issues on justice and home affairs, which people said we were never going to get.

807
01:08:05,738 --> 01:08:06,018
[SPEAKER_18]: All right.

808
01:08:06,238 --> 01:08:07,520
[SPEAKER_18]: And I got those negotiations.

809
01:08:07,540 --> 01:08:16,491
[SPEAKER_06]: Can you remind us how many times you told us, after you became Prime Minister, that there would not be a general election until 2020?

810
01:08:19,508 --> 01:08:22,332
[SPEAKER_06]: You did, didn't you?

811
01:08:22,352 --> 01:08:26,858
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, I got to a grand total of six times on which you or your spokesman said there wouldn't be one.

812
01:08:27,238 --> 01:08:29,641
[SPEAKER_18]: And I said there wouldn't be a general election.

813
01:08:30,022 --> 01:08:43,660
[SPEAKER_18]: And after I became Prime Minister, I felt that the most important thing for the country was the stability and getting on with triggering the Article 50 so that we made sure that we were delivering on that vote on Brexit.

814
01:08:43,640 --> 01:08:51,611
[SPEAKER_18]: What became clear when we were going through that process is that other parties want to frustrate that process of those Brexit negotiations.

815
01:08:52,131 --> 01:08:55,396
[SPEAKER_18]: We have the Liberal Democrats wanting a second referendum.

816
01:08:55,416 --> 01:08:57,058
[SPEAKER_18]: That's all happened since March, has it?

817
01:08:57,078 --> 01:09:00,623
[SPEAKER_18]: We have the... Well, actually, it was March.

818
01:09:00,643 --> 01:09:06,230
[SPEAKER_18]: It was in March that I triggered Article 50 by writing the letter to the European Council.

819
01:09:06,250 --> 01:09:13,039
[SPEAKER_06]: It was in March you told us we didn't need to have a general election because it would destabilise the country until 2020.

820
01:09:13,407 --> 01:09:31,046
[SPEAKER_18]: And what became clear as we were looking through those negotiations, as we started those negotiations, started the process of triggering them, what became clear, increasingly clear, as is clear in this election campaign, is the desire of other parties to frustrate the will of the British people.

821
01:09:31,487 --> 01:09:37,573
[SPEAKER_18]: That's why I thought it was right to go out for an election.

822
01:09:37,593 --> 01:09:41,237
[SPEAKER_06]: Prime Minister, are you somebody who takes responsibility for their mistakes?

823
01:09:42,095 --> 01:09:44,598
[SPEAKER_18]: I take responsibility for the decisions I make, Jeremy.

824
01:09:44,838 --> 01:09:45,078
[SPEAKER_06]: Right.

825
01:09:45,779 --> 01:09:48,222
[SPEAKER_06]: So you have been how many years in government now?

826
01:09:49,303 --> 01:09:49,823
[SPEAKER_06]: In government?

827
01:09:49,943 --> 01:09:50,124
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes.

828
01:09:50,164 --> 01:09:52,907
[SPEAKER_18]: I've been in government since 2010, so seven years in government.

829
01:09:53,007 --> 01:09:58,012
[SPEAKER_06]: Seven years in government, and you'll recall the manifesto promises on immigration.

830
01:09:58,032 --> 01:09:58,673
[SPEAKER_06]: Indeed I do.

831
01:09:58,733 --> 01:10:01,516
[SPEAKER_06]: You've repeated them, in fact, in this manifesto.

832
01:10:01,536 --> 01:10:02,277
[SPEAKER_06]: Yes, yes.

833
01:10:02,297 --> 01:10:05,520
[SPEAKER_06]: Said the same thing again because you've failed

834
01:10:05,500 --> 01:10:08,945
[SPEAKER_06]: In your capacity, six of those seven years, you were Home Secretary, weren't you?

835
01:10:08,965 --> 01:10:09,606
[SPEAKER_06]: I was indeed.

836
01:10:09,867 --> 01:10:10,067
[SPEAKER_06]: Yeah.

837
01:10:10,427 --> 01:10:23,948
[SPEAKER_06]: Immigration was your main task, to get it down to what you promised in the manifesto, which was 100,000 or less non-EU immigrants per year net.

838
01:10:24,923 --> 01:10:25,924
[SPEAKER_06]: You didn't do that, did you?

839
01:10:26,585 --> 01:10:27,126
[SPEAKER_18]: Net migration?

840
01:10:27,186 --> 01:10:28,208
[SPEAKER_18]: No, we didn't achieve that.

841
01:10:28,788 --> 01:10:31,753
[SPEAKER_06]: We did... Can you just tell us what it is now?

842
01:10:32,213 --> 01:10:35,197
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes, it was 248,000 in the last set of figures.

843
01:10:35,958 --> 01:10:40,324
[SPEAKER_06]: What we saw was the figures coming... Non-EU migrants?

844
01:10:40,344 --> 01:10:40,525
[SPEAKER_18]: Sorry?

845
01:10:40,545 --> 01:10:40,985
[SPEAKER_18]: Non-EU migrants?

846
01:10:41,086 --> 01:10:42,928
[SPEAKER_18]: Was about 170,000, 175,000.

847
01:10:43,068 --> 01:10:46,493
[SPEAKER_06]: It's 175,000 according to the latest figures, yes.

848
01:10:46,473 --> 01:10:52,473
[SPEAKER_18]: What we saw in immigration figures was it started to come down, then they did go up and now they're starting to come down again.

849
01:10:53,115 --> 01:10:56,466
[SPEAKER_18]: What we will have when we leave the EU is the...

850
01:10:56,800 --> 01:10:58,222
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes.

851
01:10:58,242 --> 01:11:00,144
[SPEAKER_18]: Jeremy, I'm not sitting here saying it wasn't.

852
01:11:00,204 --> 01:11:07,392
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm accepting that what we had to do was to ensure that we were rooting out abuse in the system.

853
01:11:07,892 --> 01:11:13,419
[SPEAKER_18]: But there is no single moment where you take one measure which changes the immigration figures.

854
01:11:13,939 --> 01:11:19,045
[SPEAKER_18]: It is a constant work to ensure that you're dealing with immigration

855
01:11:19,025 --> 01:11:21,969
[SPEAKER_18]: and ensuring there is no more abuse in the system.

856
01:11:22,450 --> 01:11:23,531
[SPEAKER_18]: There's more work to be done.

857
01:11:24,132 --> 01:11:34,687
[SPEAKER_18]: We will, of course, have another tool to do this when we leave the European Union, because we'll be able to introduce rules for people coming from within the European Union.

858
01:11:34,707 --> 01:11:36,129
[SPEAKER_18]: But this will be a constant work.

859
01:11:37,571 --> 01:11:41,556
[SPEAKER_06]: Who won't be able to come to this country under your new rules?

860
01:11:42,532 --> 01:11:46,778
[SPEAKER_18]: Well, we're working at the moment on what those new rules should be in terms of...

861
01:11:46,798 --> 01:11:48,320
[SPEAKER_06]: So you still don't have any idea?

862
01:11:48,340 --> 01:11:50,964
[SPEAKER_18]: No, it's not about that.

863
01:11:50,984 --> 01:11:53,627
[SPEAKER_18]: We have a set of rules for people from outside the European Union.

864
01:11:54,068 --> 01:12:05,604
[SPEAKER_18]: We will look at the requirements for... One of the things we do is ensure that it's possible for people to be brought in where there are skill shortages, where there is a need for people to come to work.

865
01:12:05,724 --> 01:12:07,567
[SPEAKER_06]: And what's the damage going to be to the economy?

866
01:12:07,587 --> 01:12:08,488
[SPEAKER_06]: Have you worked that out?

867
01:12:09,397 --> 01:12:18,908
[SPEAKER_18]: I think one of the crucial things we need to do in this country is ensure that actually we are enabling people here in the UK to be skilled up to do jobs.

868
01:12:19,429 --> 01:12:28,239
[SPEAKER_18]: I think sometimes what we've seen is people being brought in from overseas because we haven't done sufficient in this country.

869
01:12:28,319 --> 01:12:30,201
[SPEAKER_18]: That's why I think technical education is so important.

870
01:12:30,221 --> 01:12:38,070
[SPEAKER_06]: Your friend George Osborne, or your friend until you sacked him, the Chancellor of the Exchequer, George Osborne, says this policy is economically illiterate.

871
01:12:39,215 --> 01:12:41,378
[SPEAKER_18]: It's a policy which will actually...

872
01:12:41,438 --> 01:12:42,479
[SPEAKER_18]: He should know, shouldn't he?

873
01:12:42,499 --> 01:12:51,190
[SPEAKER_18]: It's a policy which ensures that we are recognising the concerns that people in this country have about uncontrolled immigration.

874
01:12:51,770 --> 01:12:54,193
[SPEAKER_18]: Controlling immigration is important.

875
01:12:54,434 --> 01:13:05,307
[SPEAKER_18]: It's important for a number of reasons, but one of the reasons it's important is because uncontrolled migration has an impact on wages at the lower end of the income scale.

876
01:13:05,287 --> 01:13:07,610
[SPEAKER_18]: People feel an impact from that.

877
01:13:07,970 --> 01:13:12,556
[SPEAKER_18]: That's why I think it's so important that we keep working at this and we keep that aim.

878
01:13:12,576 --> 01:13:13,697
[SPEAKER_06]: And you say it's much easier.

879
01:13:13,878 --> 01:13:17,823
[SPEAKER_06]: It'll be much easier once we've left the European Union, won't it?

880
01:13:17,843 --> 01:13:22,609
[SPEAKER_18]: We will be able to introduce rules for people coming from within the European Union once we've left.

881
01:13:23,049 --> 01:13:27,975
[SPEAKER_18]: That's been a piece of the work on immigration that hasn't been available to us.

882
01:13:27,995 --> 01:13:31,800
[SPEAKER_06]: How much of our money are you prepared to give Brussels in order to get a deal?

883
01:13:32,573 --> 01:13:36,265
[SPEAKER_18]: I don't think it's going to be about paying over money to get a deal.

884
01:13:36,727 --> 01:13:39,536
[SPEAKER_18]: What I think is important is that... You're not prepared to pay anything.

885
01:13:39,597 --> 01:13:41,603
[SPEAKER_06]: I mean, David Davis said he'd walk away at 100,000.

886
01:13:41,623 --> 01:13:43,369
[SPEAKER_06]: 100 million.

887
01:13:43,650 --> 01:13:44,794
[SPEAKER_06]: 100 billion, sorry.

888
01:13:44,909 --> 01:13:52,216
[SPEAKER_18]: We have made clear, I've put it in the manifesto, that we will look for a fair... Would you pay 100 billion to leave the European Union?

889
01:13:52,236 --> 01:13:56,880
[SPEAKER_18]: That we will put a fair settlement, look for a fair settlement of our rights and obligations.

890
01:13:57,280 --> 01:14:03,466
[SPEAKER_18]: There are a number of figures that are being quoted and being around, a number of them coming from the European Union.

891
01:14:03,486 --> 01:14:04,747
[SPEAKER_18]: Have you got the figure in your head?

892
01:14:05,127 --> 01:14:07,429
[SPEAKER_18]: A number coming from the European Union itself.

893
01:14:07,910 --> 01:14:09,751
[SPEAKER_18]: We will look at our rights and obligations.

894
01:14:09,831 --> 01:14:14,916
[SPEAKER_06]: Have you got a figure in your head as to how much it's worth paying to get out of this club?

895
01:14:14,896 --> 01:14:18,682
[SPEAKER_18]: It isn't a question of what it's worth paying to get out.

896
01:14:19,123 --> 01:14:36,631
[SPEAKER_18]: It's a question of what is going to be the right deal for us to leave the European Union, which will stop us from paying huge sums of money into the EU every single year, which will enable that we have control of our money and our borders and our laws.

897
01:14:36,651 --> 01:14:42,540
[SPEAKER_06]: But you wouldn't walk out, as David Davis says he would, if there was a request for £100 billion?

898
01:14:42,520 --> 01:14:43,543
[SPEAKER_18]: You wouldn't walk out.

899
01:14:43,563 --> 01:14:50,320
[SPEAKER_18]: We will be there to negotiate the right deal, but what I have said is no deal is better than a bad deal.

900
01:14:50,782 --> 01:14:54,451
[SPEAKER_18]: We have to be prepared to walk out.

901
01:14:54,471 --> 01:14:58,943
[SPEAKER_06]: So you are prepared to walk away from the European Union with no deal.

902
01:14:59,210 --> 01:15:01,394
[SPEAKER_18]: No deal is better than a bad deal.

903
01:15:01,695 --> 01:15:04,441
[SPEAKER_18]: And let me just tell you... That wasn't exactly my question.

904
01:15:04,561 --> 01:15:17,387
[SPEAKER_18]: My question was, are you prepared to walk away... By definition, if we're prepared to say, if I'm prepared to say that no deal is better than a bad deal, I want to get a good deal from the European Union.

905
01:15:17,367 --> 01:15:21,874
[SPEAKER_18]: What I don't want is the sort of bad deal that some people are talking about.

906
01:15:21,914 --> 01:15:27,724
[SPEAKER_18]: If you think about it, some people in Europe are talking about punishing us, and that would be a bad deal for us.

907
01:15:28,084 --> 01:15:37,079
[SPEAKER_18]: Some people here in the UK talk as if they're willing to do anything to sign up to a deal with the European Union, and that would be a bad deal for us as well.

908
01:15:37,279 --> 01:15:41,606
[SPEAKER_06]: So you are prepared to leave the European Union with no deal?

909
01:15:42,347 --> 01:15:44,691
[SPEAKER_18]: As I say, no deal would be better than a bad deal.

910
01:15:45,278 --> 01:15:49,090
[SPEAKER_06]: You are prepared to leave the European Union with no deal.

911
01:15:49,110 --> 01:15:50,455
[SPEAKER_18]: I think you can take it, Jeremy.

912
01:15:50,495 --> 01:15:52,622
[SPEAKER_18]: No deal would be better than a bad deal.

913
01:15:52,742 --> 01:15:58,039
[SPEAKER_18]: Yes, you've said that repeatedly.

914
01:15:59,791 --> 01:16:02,876
[SPEAKER_18]: I'm not prepared to sign up to a bad deal for the UK.

915
01:16:03,136 --> 01:16:03,897
[SPEAKER_18]: Now, I believe...

916
01:16:03,917 --> 01:16:05,399
[SPEAKER_06]: So you are prepared to walk away?

917
01:16:05,640 --> 01:16:07,943
[SPEAKER_18]: I think you have to.

918
01:16:08,344 --> 01:16:15,935
[SPEAKER_18]: In negotiations, you have to recognise that you're prepared, that you're not in there to get a deal at any price.

919
01:16:16,596 --> 01:16:19,320
[SPEAKER_18]: We're in there to get the best deal for the United Kingdom.

920
01:16:19,841 --> 01:16:28,313
[SPEAKER_18]: And actually, I'm optimistic about that, because I think that in the European Union, they will want to continue their relationship with us as well.

921
01:16:28,293 --> 01:16:31,861
[SPEAKER_06]: You can be as optimistic as you like, but you might have to walk away from it.

922
01:16:33,084 --> 01:16:40,181
[SPEAKER_18]: What I will be doing is, as we heard in the earlier session, what I'll be doing is being a difficult woman and ensuring that we're negotiating hard.

923
01:16:40,562 --> 01:16:44,832
[SPEAKER_06]: But... Theresa May, thank you very much.

924
01:16:45,012 --> 01:16:45,694
[SPEAKER_06]: Thank you.

925
01:17:18,749 --> 01:17:19,451
[SPEAKER_05]: Welcome back.

926
01:17:19,591 --> 01:17:23,259
[SPEAKER_05]: You've been watching May versus Corbyn, the battle for number 10.

927
01:17:23,620 --> 01:17:36,049
[SPEAKER_05]: The Prime Minister told our live studio audience a Conservative government would deliver a long-term sustainable solution for social care and that she's prepared to leave the EU with no deal rather than a bad one.

928
01:17:36,029 --> 01:17:45,484
[SPEAKER_06]: And that Mr Corbyn said that immigration would probably fall under a Labour government, and that leadership is not about being high and mighty, but about getting to know people.

929
01:17:46,104 --> 01:17:50,952
[SPEAKER_06]: If you want to watch again, you can watch the whole programme on 4.7 at five past one tonight.

930
01:17:51,072 --> 01:17:54,257
[SPEAKER_06]: It'll also be available on demand at all four.

931
01:17:55,098 --> 01:18:02,430
[SPEAKER_05]: You'll also be able to see the full program at Sky News Catch Up on the Sky News app on Sky Q and on Sky Go.

932
01:18:02,630 --> 01:18:09,902
[SPEAKER_05]: And of course, coverage of the battle for number 10 continues on Sky News TV and mobile.

933
01:18:09,922 --> 01:18:13,407
[SPEAKER_06]: There are nine days of campaigning left before polling day.

934
01:18:13,467 --> 01:18:15,911
[SPEAKER_06]: We hope our program has helped you decide a little.

935
01:18:16,572 --> 01:18:17,894
[SPEAKER_05]: Thank you for watching.

936
01:18:18,035 --> 01:18:19,837
[SPEAKER_05]: And thanks, too, to our audience.

937
01:18:20,278 --> 01:18:20,659
[SPEAKER_05]: Good night.

938
01:18:20,979 --> 01:18:21,460
[SPEAKER_05]: Good night.

